# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: jq-json
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] A jq program is a "filter": it takes an input, and produces an output.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] There are a lot of builtin filters for extracting a particular field of an object, or converting a number to a string, or various other standard tasks.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Filters can be combined in various ways - you can pipe the output of one filter into another filter, or collect the output of a filter into an array.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Some filters produce multiple results, for instance there's one that produces all the elements of its input array.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Piping that filter into a second runs the second filter for each element of the array.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Generally, things that would be done with loops and iteration in other languages are just done by gluing filters together in jq.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] It's important to remember that every filter has an input and an output.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Even literals like "hello" or 42 are filters - they take an input but always produce the same literal as output.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Operations that combine two filters, like addition, generally feed the same input to both and combine the results.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] So, you can implement an averaging filter as `add / length` - feeding the input array both to the `add` filter and the `length` filter and then performing the division.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] jq filters run on a stream of JSON data.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] The input to jq is parsed as a sequence of whitespace-separated JSON values which are passed through the provided filter one at a time.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] The output(s) of the filter are written to standard output, as a sequence of newline-separated JSON data.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] The simplest and most common filter (or jq program) is `.`, which is the identity operator, copying the inputs of the jq processor to the output stream.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Because the default behavior of the jq processor is to read JSON texts from the input stream, and to pretty-print outputs, the `.` program's main use is to validate and pretty-print the inputs.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] The jq programming language is quite rich and allows for much more than just validation and pretty-printing.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Note: it is important to mind the shell's quoting rules.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] As a general rule it's best to always quote (with single-quote characters on Unix shells) the jq program, as too many characters with special meaning to jq are also shell meta-characters.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] For example, `jq "foo"` will fail on most Unix shells because that will be the same as `jq foo`, which will generally fail because `foo is not defined`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] When using the Windows command shell (cmd.exe) it's best to use double quotes around your jq program when given on the command-line (instead of the `-f program-file` option), but then double-quotes in the jq program need backslash escaping.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] When using the Powershell (`powershell.exe`) or the Powershell Core (`pwsh`/`pwsh.exe`), use single-quote characters around the jq program and backslash-escaped double-quotes (`\"`) inside the jq program.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Note: jq allows user-defined functions, but every jq program must have a top-level expression.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Instead, the filter is run once using `null` as the input.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] This is useful when using jq as a simple calculator or to construct JSON data from scratch.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Instead, each line of text is passed to the filter as a string.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] If combined with `--slurp`, then the entire input is passed to the filter as a single long string.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Instead of running the filter for each JSON object in the input, read the entire input stream into a large array and run the filter just once.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] By default, jq pretty-prints JSON output.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Using this option will result in more compact output by instead putting each JSON object on a single line.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] With this option, if the filter's result is a string then it will be written directly to standard output rather than being formatted as a JSON string with quotes.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] This can be useful for making jq filters talk to non-JSON-based systems.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Like `-r` but jq will print NUL instead of newline after each output.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] This can be useful when the values being output can contain newlines.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] When the output value contains NUL, jq exits with non-zero code.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Like `-r` but jq won't print a newline after each output.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] jq usually outputs non-ASCII Unicode codepoints as UTF-8, even if the input specified them as escape sequences (like "\u03bc").
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Using this option, you can force jq to produce pure ASCII output with every non-ASCII character replaced with the equivalent escape sequence.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Output the fields of each object with the keys in sorted order.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] By default, jq outputs colored JSON if writing to a terminal.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] You can force it to produce color even if writing to a pipe or a file using `-C`, and disable color with `-M`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] When the `NO_COLOR` environment variable is not empty, jq disables colored output by default, but you can enable it by `-C`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Colors can be configured with the `JQ_COLORS` environment variable (see below).
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Use a tab for each indentation level instead of two spaces.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Use the given number of spaces (no more than 7) for indentation.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Flush the output after each JSON object is printed (useful if you're piping a slow data source into jq and piping jq's output elsewhere).
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Parse the input in streaming fashion, outputting arrays of path and leaf values (scalars and empty arrays or empty objects).
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] This is useful for processing very large inputs.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Use this in conjunction with filtering and the `reduce` and `foreach` syntax to reduce large inputs incrementally.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Like `--stream`, but invalid JSON inputs yield array values where the first element is the error and the second is a path.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Invalid JSON inputs produce no error values when `--stream` without `--stream-errors`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Use the `application/json-seq` MIME type scheme for separating JSON texts in jq's input and output.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] This means that an ASCII RS (record separator) character is printed before each value on output and an ASCII LF (line feed) is printed after every output.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Input JSON texts that fail to parse are ignored (but warned about), discarding all subsequent input until the next RS.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] This mode also parses the output of jq without the `--seq` option.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Read the filter from a file rather than from a command line, like awk's -f option.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] This changes the filter argument to be interpreted as a filename, instead of the source of a program.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Prepend `directory` to the search list for modules.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] If this option is used then no builtin search list is used.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] This option passes a value to the jq program as a predefined variable.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] If you run jq with `--arg foo bar`, then `$foo` is available in the program and has the value `"bar"`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Note that `value` will be treated as a string, so `--arg foo 123` will bind `$foo` to `"123"`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Named arguments are also available to the jq program as `$ARGS.named`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] When the name is not a valid identifier, this is the only way to access it.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] This option passes a JSON-encoded value to the jq program as a predefined variable.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] If you run jq with `--argjson foo 123`, then `$foo` is available in the program and has the value `123`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] This option reads all the JSON texts in the named file and binds an array of the parsed JSON values to the given global variable.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] If you run jq with `--slurpfile foo bar`, then `$foo` is available in the program and has an array whose elements correspond to the texts in the file named `bar`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] This option reads in the named file and binds its content to the given global variable.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] If you run jq with `--rawfile foo bar`, then `$foo` is available in the program and has a string whose content is set to the text in the file named `bar`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Remaining arguments are positional string arguments.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] These are available to the jq program as `$ARGS.positional[]`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Remaining arguments are positional JSON text arguments.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Sets the exit status of jq to 0 if the last output value was neither `false` nor `null`, 1 if the last output value was either `false` or `null`, or 4 if no valid result was ever produced.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Normally jq exits with 2 if there was any usage problem or system error, 3 if there was a jq program compile error, or 0 if the jq program ran.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Another way to set the exit status is with the `halt_error` builtin function.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Windows users using WSL, MSYS2, or Cygwin, should use this option when using a native jq.exe, otherwise jq will turn newlines (LFs) into carriage-return-then-newline (CRLF).
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Output the jq version and exit with zero.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Output the build configuration of jq and exit with zero.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] This output has no supported format or structure and may change without notice in future releases.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Remaining arguments are not interpreted as options.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Runs the tests in the given file or standard input.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] This must be the last option given and does not honor all preceding options.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] The input consists of comment lines, empty lines, and program lines followed by one input line, as many lines of output as are expected (one per output), and a terminating empty line.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Compilation failure tests start with a line containing only `%%FAIL`, then a line containing the program to compile, then a line containing an error message to compare to the actual.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Be warned that this option can change backwards-incompatibly.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] This filter takes its input and produces the same value as output.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Since jq by default pretty-prints all output, a trivial program consisting of nothing but `.` can be used to format JSON output from, say, `curl`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Although the identity filter never modifies the value of its input, jq processing can sometimes make it appear as though it does.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] This is because, in the process of parsing the number, this particular version of jq has converted it to an IEEE754 double-precision representation, losing precision.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] The way in which jq handles numbers has changed over time and further changes are likely within the parameters set by the relevant JSON standards.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Moreover, build configuration options can alter how jq processes numbers.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] (1) Any arithmetic operation on a number that has not already been converted to an IEEE754 double precision representation will trigger a conversion to the IEEE754 representation.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] (2) jq will attempt to maintain the original decimal precision of number literals (if the `--disable-decnum` build configuration option was not used), but in expressions such `1E1234567890`, precision will be lost if the exponent is too large.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] (3) Comparisons are carried out using the untruncated big decimal representation of numbers if available, as illustrated in one of the following examples.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] The examples below use the builtin function `have_decnum` in order to demonstrate the expected effects of using / not using the `--disable-decnum` build configuration option, and also to allow automated tests derived from these examples to pass regardless of whether that option is used.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] The simplest *useful* filter has the form `.foo`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] When given a JSON object (aka dictionary or hash) as input, `.foo` produces the value at the key "foo" if the key is present, or null otherwise.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] A filter of the form `.foo.bar` is equivalent to `.foo | .bar`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] The `.foo` syntax only works for simple, identifier-like keys, that is, keys that are all made of alphanumeric characters and underscore, and which do not start with a digit.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] If the key contains special characters or starts with a digit, you need to surround it with double quotes like this: `."foo$"`, or else `.["foo$"]`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Just like `.foo`, but does not output an error when `.` is not an object.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] You can also look up fields of an object using syntax like `.["foo"]` (`.foo` above is a shorthand version of this, but only for identifier-like strings).
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] When the index value is an integer, `.[<number>]` can index arrays.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Arrays are zero-based, so `.[2]` returns the third element.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Negative indices are allowed, with -1 referring to the last element, -2 referring to the next to last element, and so on.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] The `.[<number>:<number>]` syntax can be used to return a subarray of an array or substring of a string.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] The array returned by `.[10:15]` will be of length 5, containing the elements from index 10 (inclusive) to index 15 (exclusive).
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Either index may be negative (in which case it counts backwards from the end of the array), or omitted (in which case it refers to the start or end of the array).
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] If you use the `.[index]` syntax, but omit the index entirely, it will return *all* of the elements of an array.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Running `.[]` with the input `[1,2,3]` will produce the numbers as three separate results, rather than as a single array.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] A filter of the form `.foo[]` is equivalent to `.foo | .[]`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] You can also use this on an object, and it will return all the values of the object.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Note that the iterator operator is a generator of values.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Like `.[]`, but no errors will be output if . is not an array or object.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] A filter of the form `.foo[]?` is equivalent to `.foo | .[]?`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] If two filters are separated by a comma, then the same input will be fed into both and the two filters' output value streams will be concatenated in order: first, all of the outputs produced by the left expression, and then all of the outputs produced by the right.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] For instance, filter `.foo, .bar`, produces both the "foo" fields and "bar" fields as separate outputs.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] The `,` operator is one way to construct generators.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] The | operator combines two filters by feeding the output(s) of the one on the left into the input of the one on the right.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] It's similar to the Unix shell's pipe, if you're used to that.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] If the one on the left produces multiple results, the one on the right will be run for each of those results.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] So, the expression `.[] | .foo` retrieves the "foo" field of each element of the input array.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] This is a cartesian product, which can be surprising.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Note that `.a.b.c` is the same as `.a | .b | .c`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Note too that `.` is the input value at the particular stage in a "pipeline", specifically: where the `.` expression appears.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Thus `.a | . | .b` is the same as `.a.b`, as the `.` in the middle refers to whatever value `.a` produced.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Parenthesis work as a grouping operator just as in any typical programming language.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] jq supports the same set of datatypes as JSON - numbers, strings, booleans, arrays, objects (which in JSON-speak are hashes with only string keys), and "null".
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Booleans, null, strings and numbers are written the same way as in JSON.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Just like everything else in jq, these simple values take an input and produce an output - `42` is a valid jq expression that takes an input, ignores it, and returns 42 instead.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Numbers in jq are internally represented by their IEEE754 double precision approximation.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Any arithmetic operation with numbers, whether they are literals or results of previous filters, will produce a double precision floating point result.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] However, when parsing a literal jq will store the original literal string.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] If no mutation is applied to this value then it will make to the output in its original form, even if conversion to double would result in a loss.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] As in JSON, `[]` is used to construct arrays, as in `[1,2,3]`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] The elements of the arrays can be any jq expression, including a pipeline.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] All of the results produced by all of the expressions are collected into one big array.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] If you have a filter `X` that produces four results, then the expression `[X]` will produce a single result, an array of four elements.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Like JSON, `{}` is for constructing objects (aka dictionaries or hashes), as in: `{"a": 42, "b": 17}`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] If the keys are "identifier-like", then the quotes can be left off, as in `{a:42, b:17}`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Variable references as key expressions use the value of the variable as the key.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Key expressions other than constant literals, identifiers, or variable references, need to be parenthesized, e.g., `{("a"+"b"):59}`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] The value can be any expression (although you may need to wrap it in parentheses if, for example, it contains colons), which gets applied to the {} expression's input (remember, all filters have an input and an output).
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] will produce the JSON object `{"foo": 42}` if given the JSON object `{"bar":42, "baz":43}` as its input.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Because that is so common, there's a shortcut syntax for it: `{user, title}`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] If one of the expressions produces multiple results, multiple dictionaries will be produced.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Putting parentheses around the key means it will be evaluated as an expression.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Variable references as keys use the value of the variable as the key.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Recursively descends `.`, producing every value.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] This is the same as the zero-argument `recurse` builtin (see below).
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] This is intended to resemble the XPath `//` operator.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] Note that `..a` does not work; use `.. | .a` instead.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] In the example below we use `.. | .a?` to find all the values of object keys "a" in any object found "below" `.`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p01] This is particularly useful in conjunction with `path(EXP)` (also see below) and the `?` operator.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Some jq operators (for instance, `+`) do different things depending on the type of their arguments (arrays, numbers, etc.).
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] However, jq never does implicit type conversions.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] If you try to add a string to an object you'll get an error message and no result.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Please note that all numbers are converted to IEEE754 double precision floating point representation.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Arithmetic and logical operators are working with these converted doubles.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Results of all such operations are also limited to the double precision.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The only exception to this behaviour of number is a snapshot of original number literal.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] When a number which originally was provided as a literal is never mutated until the end of the program then it is printed to the output in its original literal form.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] This also includes cases when the original literal would be truncated when converted to the IEEE754 double precision floating point number.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The operator `+` takes two filters, applies them both to the same input, and adds the results together.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] `null` can be added to any value, and returns the other value unchanged.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] As well as normal arithmetic subtraction on numbers, the `-` operator can be used on arrays to remove all occurrences of the second array's elements from the first array.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] These infix operators behave as expected when given two numbers.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Multiplying a string by a number produces the concatenation of that string that many times.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Dividing a string by another splits the first using the second as separators.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Multiplying two objects will merge them recursively: this works like addition but if both objects contain a value for the same key, and the values are objects, the two are merged with the same strategy.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The builtin function `abs` is defined naively as: `if . < 0 then - . else . end`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] For numeric input, this is the absolute value.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] See the section on the identity filter for the implications of this definition for numeric input.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] To compute the absolute value of a number as a floating point number, you may wish use `fabs`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The builtin function `utf8bytelength` outputs the number of bytes used to encode a string in UTF-8.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The builtin function `keys`, when given an object, returns its keys in an array.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The keys are sorted "alphabetically", by unicode codepoint order.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] This is not an order that makes particular sense in any particular language, but you can count on it being the same for any two objects with the same set of keys, regardless of locale settings.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] When `keys` is given an array, it returns the valid indices for that array: the integers from 0 to length-1.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `keys_unsorted` function is just like `keys`, but if the input is an object then the keys will not be sorted, instead the keys will roughly be in insertion order.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The builtin function `has` returns whether the input object has the given key, or the input array has an element at the given index.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] `has($key)` has the same effect as checking whether `$key` is a member of the array returned by `keys`, although `has` will be faster.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The builtin function `in` returns whether or not the input key is in the given object, or the input index corresponds to an element in the given array.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] It is, essentially, an inversed version of `has`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] For any filter `f`, `map(f)` and `map_values(f)` apply `f` to each of the values in the input array or object, that is, to the values of `.[]`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] In the absence of errors, `map(f)` always outputs an array whereas `map_values(f)` outputs an array if given an array, or an object if given an object.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] When the input to `map_values(f)` is an object, the output object has the same keys as the input object except for those keys whose values when piped to `f` produce no values at all.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The key difference between `map(f)` and `map_values(f)` is that the former simply forms an array from all the values of `($x|f)` for each value, `$x`, in the input array or object, but `map_values(f)` only uses `first($x|f)`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Specifically, for object inputs, `map_values(f)` constructs the output object by examining in turn the value of `first(.[$k]|f)` for each key, `$k`, of the input.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] If this expression produces no values, then the corresponding key will be dropped; otherwise, the output object will have that value at the key, `$k`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Here are some examples to clarify the behavior of `map` and `map_values` when applied to arrays.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] In fact, these are their implementations.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Emit the projection of the input object or array defined by the specified sequence of path expressions, such that if `p` is any one of these specifications, then `(. | p)` will evaluate to the same value as `(. | pick(pathexps) | p)`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] For arrays, negative indices and `.[m:n]` specifications should not be used.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Outputs array representations of the given path expression in `.`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The outputs are arrays of strings (object keys) and/or numbers (array indices).
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Path expressions are jq expressions like `.a`, but also `.[]`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] There are two types of path expressions: ones that can match exactly, and ones that cannot.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] For example, `.a.b.c` is an exact match path expression, while `.a[].b` is not.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] `path(exact_path_expression)` will produce the array representation of the path expression even if it does not exist in `.`, if `.` is `null` or an array or an object.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] `path(pattern)` will produce array representations of the paths matching `pattern` if the paths exist in `.`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Note that the path expressions are not different from normal expressions.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The expression `path(..|select(type=="boolean"))` outputs all the paths to boolean values in `.`, and only those paths.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The builtin function `del` removes a key and its corresponding value from an object.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The builtin function `getpath` outputs the values in `.` found at each path in `PATHS`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The builtin function `setpath` sets the `PATHS` in `.` to `VALUE`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The builtin function `delpaths` deletes the `PATHS` in `.`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] `PATHS` must be an array of paths, where each path is an array of strings and numbers.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] These functions convert between an object and an array of key-value pairs.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] If `to_entries` is passed an object, then for each `k: v` entry in the input, the output array includes `{"key": k, "value": v}`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] `from_entries` does the opposite conversion, and `with_entries(f)` is a shorthand for `to_entries | map(f) | from_entries`, useful for doing some operation to all keys and values of an object.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The function `select(f)` produces its input unchanged if `f` returns true for that input, and produces no output otherwise.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] These built-ins select only inputs that are arrays, objects, iterables (arrays or objects), booleans, numbers, normal numbers, finite numbers, strings, null, non-null values, and non-iterables, respectively.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Produces an error with the input value, or with the message given as the argument.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Errors can be caught with try/catch; see below.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Stops the jq program with no further outputs. jq will exit with exit status `0`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Stops the jq program with no further outputs.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The input will be printed on `stderr` as raw output (i.e., strings will not have double quotes) with no decoration, not even a newline.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The given `exit_code` (defaulting to `5`) will be jq's exit status.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] For example, `"Error: something went wrong\n"|halt_error(1)`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Produces an object with a "file" key and a "line" key, with the filename and line number where `$__loc__` occurs, as values.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] `paths` outputs the paths to all the elements in its input (except it does not output the empty list, representing . itself).
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] `paths(f)` outputs the paths to any values for which `f` is `true`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] That is, `paths(type == "number")` outputs the paths to all numeric values.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The filter `add` takes as input an array, and produces as output the elements of the array added together.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] This might mean summed, concatenated or merged depending on the types of the elements of the input array - the rules are the same as those for the `+` operator (described above).
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] If the input is an empty array, `add` returns `null`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] `add(generator)` operates on the given generator rather than the input.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The filter `any` takes as input an array of boolean values, and produces `true` as output if any of the elements of the array are `true`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] If the input is an empty array, `any` returns `false`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `any(condition)` form applies the given condition to the elements of the input array.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `any(generator; condition)` form applies the given condition to all the outputs of the given generator.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The filter `all` takes as input an array of boolean values, and produces `true` as output if all of the elements of the array are `true`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `all(condition)` form applies the given condition to the elements of the input array.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `all(generator; condition)` form applies the given condition to all the outputs of the given generator.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] If the input is an empty array, `all` returns `true`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The filter `flatten` takes as input an array of nested arrays, and produces a flat array in which all arrays inside the original array have been recursively replaced by their values.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] You can pass an argument to it to specify how many levels of nesting to flatten.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] `flatten(2)` is like `flatten`, but going only up to two levels deep.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `range` function produces a range of numbers.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] `range(4; 10)` produces 6 numbers, from 4 (inclusive) to 10 (exclusive).
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The numbers are produced as separate outputs.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Use `[range(4; 10)]` to get a range as an array.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The one argument form generates numbers from 0 to the given number, with an increment of 1.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The two argument form generates numbers from `from` to `upto` with an increment of 1.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The three argument form generates numbers `from` to `upto` with an increment of `by`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `floor` function returns the floor of its numeric input.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `sqrt` function returns the square root of its numeric input.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `tonumber` function parses its input as a number.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] It will convert correctly-formatted strings to their numeric equivalent, leave numbers alone, and give an error on all other input.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `toboolean` function parses its input as a boolean.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] It will convert correctly-formatted strings to their boolean equivalent, leave booleans alone, and give an error on all other input.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `tostring` function prints its input as a string.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Strings are left unchanged, and all other values are JSON-encoded.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `type` function returns the type of its argument as a string, which is one of null, boolean, number, string, array or object.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Some arithmetic operations can yield infinities and "not a number" (NaN) values.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `isinfinite` builtin returns `true` if its input is infinite.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `isnan` builtin returns `true` if its input is a NaN.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `infinite` builtin returns a positive infinite value.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `isnormal` builtin returns true if its input is a normal number.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Note that division by zero raises an error.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Currently most arithmetic operations operating on infinities, NaNs, and sub-normals do not raise errors.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `sort` functions sorts its input, which must be an array.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The ordering for objects is a little complex: first they're compared by comparing their sets of keys (as arrays in sorted order), and if their keys are equal then the values are compared key by key.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] `sort_by` may be used to sort by a particular field of an object, or by applying any jq filter.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] `sort_by(f)` compares two elements by comparing the result of `f` on each element.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] When `f` produces multiple values, it firstly compares the first values, and the second values if the first values are equal, and so on.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] `group_by(.foo)` takes as input an array, groups the elements having the same `.foo` field into separate arrays, and produces all of these arrays as elements of a larger array, sorted by the value of the `.foo` field.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Any jq expression, not just a field access, may be used in place of `.foo`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The sorting order is the same as described in the `sort` function above.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Find the minimum or maximum element of the input array.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `min_by(path_exp)` and `max_by(path_exp)` functions allow you to specify a particular field or property to examine, e.g.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] `min_by(.foo)` finds the object with the smallest `foo` field.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `unique` function takes as input an array and produces an array of the same elements, in sorted order, with duplicates removed.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `unique_by(path_exp)` function will keep only one element for each value obtained by applying the argument.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Think of it as making an array by taking one element out of every group produced by `group`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The filter `contains(b)` will produce true if b is completely contained within the input.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] A string B is contained in a string A if B is a substring of A.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] An array B is contained in an array A if all elements in B are contained in any element in A.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] An object B is contained in object A if all of the values in B are contained in the value in A with the same key.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] All other types are assumed to be contained in each other if they are equal.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Outputs an array containing the indices in `.` where `s` occurs.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The input may be an array, in which case if `s` is an array then the indices output will be those where all elements in `.` match those of `s`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Outputs the index of the first (`index`) or last (`rindex`) occurrence of `s` in the input.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The filter `inside(b)` will produce true if the input is completely contained within b.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] It is, essentially, an inversed version of `contains`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Outputs `true` if . starts with the given string argument.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Outputs `true` if . ends with the given string argument.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Outputs all combinations of the elements of the arrays in the input array.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] If given an argument `n`, it outputs all combinations of `n` repetitions of the input array.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Outputs its input with the given prefix string removed, if it starts with it.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Outputs its input with the given suffix string removed, if it ends with it.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Outputs its input with the given string removed at both ends, if it starts or ends with it.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] `trim` trims both leading and trailing whitespace.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] `ltrim` trims only leading (left side) whitespace.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] `rtrim` trims only trailing (right side) whitespace.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Whitespace characters are the usual `" "`, `"\n"` `"\t"`, `"\r"` and also all characters in the Unicode character database with the whitespace property.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Note that what considers whitespace might change in the future.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Converts an input string into an array of the string's codepoint numbers.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Splits an input string on the separator argument.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] `split` can also split on regex matches when called with two arguments (see the regular expressions section below).
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Joins the array of elements given as input, using the argument as separator.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] It is the inverse of `split`: that is, running `split("foo") | join("foo")` over any input string returns said input string.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Numbers and booleans in the input are converted to strings.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Null values are treated as empty strings.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Arrays and objects in the input are not supported.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Emit a copy of the input string with its alphabetic characters (a-z and A-Z) converted to the specified case.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `while(cond; update)` function allows you to repeatedly apply an update to `.` until `cond` is false.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Note that `while(cond; update)` is internally defined as a recursive jq function.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Recursive calls within `while` will not consume additional memory if `update` produces at most one output for each input.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `repeat(exp)` function allows you to repeatedly apply expression `exp` to `.` until an error is raised.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Note that `repeat(exp)` is internally defined as a recursive jq function.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Recursive calls within `repeat` will not consume additional memory if `exp` produces at most one output for each input.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `until(cond; next)` function allows you to repeatedly apply the expression `next`, initially to `.` then to its own output, until `cond` is true.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] For example, this can be used to implement a factorial function (see below).
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Note that `until(cond; next)` is internally defined as a recursive jq function.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Recursive calls within `until()` will not consume additional memory if `next` produces at most one output for each input.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `recurse(f)` function allows you to search through a recursive structure, and extract interesting data from all levels.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Now suppose you want to extract all of the filenames present.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] You need to retrieve `.name`, `.children[].name`, `.children[].children[].name`, and so on.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] When called without an argument, `recurse` is equivalent to `recurse(.[]?)`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] `recurse(f)` is identical to `recurse(f; true)` and can be used without concerns about recursion depth.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] `recurse(f; condition)` is a generator which begins by emitting . and then emits in turn .|f, .|f|f, .|f|f|f, ... so long as the computed value satisfies the condition.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] For example, to generate all the integers, at least in principle, one could write `recurse(.+1; true)`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The recursive calls in `recurse` will not consume additional memory whenever `f` produces at most a single output for each input.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `walk(f)` function applies f recursively to every component of the input entity.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] When an array is encountered, f is first applied to its elements and then to the array itself; when an object is encountered, f is first applied to all the values and then to the object.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] In practice, f will usually test the type of its input, as illustrated in the following examples.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The first example highlights the usefulness of processing the elements of an array of arrays before processing the array itself.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The second example shows how all the keys of all the objects within the input can be considered for alteration.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] This builtin returns true if jq's build configuration includes support for preservation of input number literals.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] This builtin returns true if jq was built with "decnum", which is the current literal number preserving numeric backend implementation for jq.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] This builtin binding shows the jq executable's build configuration.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Its value has no particular format, but it can be expected to be at least the `./configure` command-line arguments, and may be enriched in the future to include the version strings for the build tooling used.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Note that this can be overridden in the command-line with `--arg` and related options.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] `$ENV` is an object representing the environment variables as set when the jq program started.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] `env` outputs an object representing jq's current environment.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] At the moment there is no builtin for setting environment variables.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Transpose a possibly jagged matrix (an array of arrays).
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Rows are padded with nulls so the result is always rectangular.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] `bsearch(x)` conducts a binary search for x in the input array.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] If the input is sorted and contains x, then `bsearch(x)` will return its index in the array; otherwise, if the array is sorted, it will return (-1 - ix) where ix is an insertion point such that the array would still be sorted after the insertion of x at ix.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] If the array is not sorted, `bsearch(x)` will return an integer that is probably of no interest.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Inside a string, you can put an expression inside parens after a backslash.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Whatever the expression returns will be interpolated into the string.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `tojson` and `fromjson` builtins dump values as JSON texts or parse JSON texts into values, respectively.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `tojson` builtin differs from `tostring` in that `tostring` returns strings unmodified, while `tojson` encodes strings as JSON strings.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `@foo` syntax is used to format and escape strings, which is useful for building URLs, documents in a language like HTML or XML, and so forth.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Calls `tostring`, see that function for details.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Applies HTML/XML escaping, by mapping the characters `<>&'"` to their entity equivalents `&lt;`, `&gt;`, `&amp;`, `&apos;`, `&quot;`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Applies percent-encoding, by mapping all reserved URI characters to a `%XX` sequence.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The inverse of `@uri`, applies percent-decoding, by mapping all `%XX` sequences to their corresponding URI characters.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The input must be an array, and it is rendered as CSV with double quotes for strings, and quotes escaped by repetition.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The input must be an array, and it is rendered as TSV (tab-separated values).
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Each input array will be printed as a single line.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Fields are separated by a single tab (ascii `0x09`).
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Input characters line-feed (ascii `0x0a`), carriage-return (ascii `0x0d`), tab (ascii `0x09`) and backslash (ascii `0x5c`) will be output as escape sequences `\n`, `\r`, `\t`, `\\` respectively.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The input is escaped suitable for use in a command-line for a POSIX shell.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] If the input is an array, the output will be a series of space-separated strings.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The input is converted to base64 as specified by RFC 4648.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The inverse of `@base64`, input is decoded as specified by RFC 4648.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Note\: If the decoded string is not UTF-8, the results are undefined.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] This syntax can be combined with string interpolation in a useful way.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] You can follow a `@foo` token with a string literal.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The contents of the string literal will *not* be escaped.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] However, all interpolations made inside that string literal will be escaped.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Note that the slashes, question mark, etc. in the URL are not escaped, as they were part of the string literal.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] jq provides some basic date handling functionality, with some high-level and low-level builtins.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] In all cases these builtins deal exclusively with time in UTC.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `fromdateiso8601` builtin parses datetimes in the ISO 8601 format to a number of seconds since the Unix epoch (1970-01-01T00:00:00Z).
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `todateiso8601` builtin does the inverse.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `fromdate` builtin parses datetime strings.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Currently `fromdate` only supports ISO 8601 datetime strings, but in the future it will attempt to parse datetime strings in more formats.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `todate` builtin is an alias for `todateiso8601`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `now` builtin outputs the current time, in seconds since the Unix epoch.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Low-level jq interfaces to the C-library time functions are also provided: `strptime`, `strftime`, `strflocaltime`, `mktime`, `gmtime`, and `localtime`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Refer to your host operating system's documentation for the format strings used by `strptime` and `strftime`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Note: these are not necessarily stable interfaces in jq, particularly as to their localization functionality.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The day of the week number may be wrong on some systems for dates before March 1st 1900, or after December 31 2099.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `localtime` builtin works like the `gmtime` builtin, but using the local timezone setting.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `mktime` builtin consumes "broken down time" representations of time output by `gmtime` and `strptime`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `strptime(fmt)` builtin parses input strings matching the `fmt` argument.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The output is in the "broken down time" representation consumed by `mktime` and output by `gmtime`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `strftime(fmt)` builtin formats a time (GMT) with the given format.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The `strflocaltime` does the same, but using the local timezone setting.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The format strings for `strptime` and `strftime` are described in typical C library documentation.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] jq may not support some or all of this date functionality on some systems.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] In particular, the `%u` and `%j` specifiers for `strptime(fmt)` are not supported on macOS.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] This builtin produces an object whose keys are computed by the given index expression applied to each value from the given stream.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] This builtin joins the values from the given stream to the given index.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The index's keys are computed by applying the given index expression to each value from the given stream.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] An array of the value in the stream and the corresponding value from the index is fed to the given join expression to produce each result.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Same as `JOIN($idx; stream; idx_expr; .)`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] This builtin joins the input `.` to the given index, applying the given index expression to `.` to compute the index key.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] The join operation is as described above.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] This builtin outputs `true` if `.` appears in the given stream, otherwise it outputs `false`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] This builtin outputs `true` if any value in the source stream appears in the second stream, otherwise it outputs `false`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Returns a list of all builtin functions in the format `name/arity`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p02] Since functions with the same name but different arities are considered separate functions, `all/0`, `all/1`, and `all/2` would all be present in the list.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The expression 'a == b' will produce 'true' if the results of evaluating a and b are equal (that is, if they represent equivalent JSON values) and 'false' otherwise.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] In particular, strings are never considered equal to numbers.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] In checking for the equality of JSON objects, the ordering of keys is irrelevant.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] If you're coming from JavaScript, please note that jq's `==` is like JavaScript's `===`, the "strict equality" operator.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] `if A then B else C end` will act the same as `B` if `A` produces a value other than false or null, but act the same as `C` otherwise.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] `if A then B end` is the same as `if A then B else . end`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] That is, the `else` branch is optional, and if absent is the same as `.`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] This also applies to `elif` with absent ending `else` branch.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Checking for false or null is a simpler notion of "truthiness" than is found in JavaScript or Python, but it means that you'll sometimes have to be more explicit about the condition you want.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] You can't test whether, e.g. a string is empty using `if .name then A else B end`; you'll need something like `if .name == "" then A else B end` instead.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] If the condition `A` produces multiple results, then `B` is evaluated once for each result that is not false or null, and `C` is evaluated once for each false or null.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] More cases can be added to an if using `elif A then B` syntax.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The comparison operators `>`, `>=`, `<=`, `<` return whether their left argument is greater than, greater than or equal to, less than or equal to or less than their right argument (respectively).
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The ordering is the same as that described for `sort`, above.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] jq supports the normal Boolean operators `and`, `or`, `not`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] They have the same standard of truth as if expressions - `false` and `null` are considered "false values", and anything else is a "true value".
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] If an operand of one of these operators produces multiple results, the operator itself will produce a result for each input.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] `not` is in fact a builtin function rather than an operator, so it is called as a filter to which things can be piped rather than with special syntax, as in `.foo and .bar | not`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] These three only produce the values `true` and `false`, and so are only useful for genuine Boolean operations, rather than the common Perl/Python/Ruby idiom of "value_that_may_be_null or default".
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] If you want to use this form of "or", picking between two values rather than evaluating a condition, see the `//` operator below.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The `//` operator produces all the values of its left-hand side that are neither `false` nor `null`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] If the left-hand side produces no values other than `false` or `null`, then `//` produces all the values of its right-hand side.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] A filter of the form `a // b` produces all the results of `a` that are not `false` or `null`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] If `a` produces no results, or no results other than `false` or `null`, then `a // b` produces the results of `b`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] This is useful for providing defaults: `.foo // 1` will evaluate to `1` if there's no `.foo` element in the input.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] It's similar to how `or` is sometimes used in Python (jq's `or` operator is reserved for strictly Boolean operations).
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Note: `some_generator // defaults_here` is not the same as `some_generator | . // defaults_here`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The latter will produce default values for all non-`false`, non-`null` values of the left-hand side, while the former will not.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Precedence rules can make this confusing.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] In `(false, null, 1) | . // 42` the left-hand side of `//` is `.`, which always produces just one value, while in `(false, null, 1) // 42` the left-hand side is a generator of three values, and since it produces a value other `false` and `null`, the default `42` is not produced.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Errors can be caught by using `try EXP catch EXP`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The first expression is executed, and if it fails then the second is executed with the error message.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The output of the handler, if any, is output as if it had been the output of the expression to try.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The `try EXP` form uses `empty` as the exception handler.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] A convenient use of try/catch is to break out of control structures like `reduce`, `foreach`, `while`, and so on.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The `break $label_name` expression will cause the program to act as though the nearest (to the left) `label $label_name` produced `empty`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The relationship between the `break` and corresponding `label` is lexical: the label has to be "visible" from the break.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The `?` operator, used as `EXP?`, is shorthand for `try EXP`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] jq uses the Oniguruma regular expression library, as do PHP, TextMate, Sublime Text, etc, so the description here will focus on jq specifics.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Oniguruma supports several flavors of regular expression, so it is important to know that jq uses the "Perl NG" (Perl with named groups) flavor.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Since REGEX must evaluate to a JSON string, some characters that are needed to form a regular expression must be escaped.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] For example, the regular expression `\s` signifying a whitespace character would be written as `"\\s"`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] To match a whitespace with the `x` flag, use `\s`, e.g.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Note that certain flags may also be specified within REGEX, e.g.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] evaluates to: `true`, `true`, `false`, `false`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Like `match`, but does not return match objects, only `true` or `false` for whether or not the regex matches the input.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Collects the named captures in a JSON object, with the name of each capture as the key, and the matched string as the corresponding value.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Emit a stream of the non-overlapping substrings of the input that match the regex in accordance with the flags, if any have been specified.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] If there is no match, the stream is empty.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] To capture all the matches for each input string, use the idiom `[ expr ]`, e.g.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] If the regex contains capturing groups, the filter emits a stream of arrays, each of which contains the captured strings.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Splits an input string on each regex match.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] For backwards compatibility, when called with a single argument, `split` splits on a string, not a regex.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] These provide the same results as their `split` counterparts, but as a stream instead of an array.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Emit the string obtained by replacing the first match of regex in the input string with `tostring`, after interpolation.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] `tostring` should be a jq string or a stream of such strings, each of which may contain references to named captures.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The named captures are, in effect, presented as a JSON object (as constructed by `capture`) to `tostring`, so a reference to a captured variable named "x" would take the form: `"\(.x)"`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] `gsub` is like `sub` but all the non-overlapping occurrences of the regex are replaced by `tostring`, after interpolation.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] If the second argument is a stream of jq strings, then `gsub` will produce a corresponding stream of JSON strings.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Variables are an absolute necessity in most programming languages, but they're relegated to an "advanced feature" in jq.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] In most languages, variables are the only means of passing around data.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] If you calculate a value, and you want to use it more than once, you'll need to store it in a variable.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] To pass a value to another part of the program, you'll need that part of the program to define a variable (as a function parameter, object member, or whatever) in which to place the data.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] It is also possible to define functions in jq, although this is is a feature whose biggest use is defining jq's standard library (many jq functions such as `map` and `select` are in fact written in jq).
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] jq has reduction operators, which are very powerful but a bit tricky.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Again, these are mostly used internally, to define some useful bits of jq's standard library.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] It may not be obvious at first, but jq is all about generators (yes, as often found in other languages).
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Some utilities are provided to help deal with generators.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Some minimal I/O support (besides reading JSON from standard input, and writing JSON to standard output) is available.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Finally, there is a module/library system.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] In jq, all filters have an input and an output, so manual plumbing is not necessary to pass a value from one part of a program to the next.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Many expressions, for instance `a + b`, pass their input to two distinct subexpressions (here `a` and `b` are both passed the same input), so variables aren't usually necessary in order to use a value twice.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] For instance, calculating the average value of an array of numbers requires a few variables in most languages - at least one to hold the array, perhaps one for each element or for a loop counter.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] In jq, it's simply `add / length` - the `add` expression is given the array and produces its sum, and the `length` expression is given the array and produces its length.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] So, there's generally a cleaner way to solve most problems in jq than defining variables.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Still, sometimes they do make things easier, so jq lets you define variables using `expression as $variable`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] We'll need a more complicated problem to find a situation where using variables actually makes our lives easier.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Suppose we have an array of blog posts, with "author" and "title" fields, and another object which is used to map author usernames to real names.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The expression `exp as $x | ...` means: for each value of expression `exp`, run the rest of the pipeline with the entire original input, and with `$x` set to that value.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Thus `as` functions as something of a foreach loop.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Just as `{foo}` is a handy way of writing `{foo: .foo}`, so `{$foo}` is a handy way of writing `{foo: $foo}`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The variable declarations in array patterns (e.g., `. as [$first, $second]`) bind to the elements of the array in from the element at index zero on up, in order.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] When there is no value at the index for an array pattern element, `null` is bound to that variable.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] For programming language theorists, it's more accurate to say that jq variables are lexically-scoped bindings.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] In particular there's no way to change the value of a binding; one can only setup a new binding with the same name, but which will not be visible where the old one was.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The destructuring alternative operator provides a concise mechanism for destructuring an input that can take one of several forms.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Suppose we have an API that returns a list of resources and events associated with them, and we want to get the user_id and timestamp of the first event for each resource.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Each alternative need not define all of the same variables, but all named variables will be available to the subsequent expression.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Additionally, if the subsequent expression returns an error, the alternative operator will attempt to try the next binding.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Errors that occur during the final alternative are passed through.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] From then on, `increment` is usable as a filter just like a builtin function (in fact, this is how many of the builtins are defined).
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Arguments are passed as *filters* (functions with no arguments), *not* as values.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The same argument may be referenced multiple times with different inputs (here `f` is run for each element of the input array).
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Arguments to a function work more like callbacks than like value arguments.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The result will be 20 because `f` is `.*2`, and during the first invocation of `f` `.` will be 5, and the second time it will be 10 (5 * 2), so the result will be 20.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Function arguments are filters, and filters expect an input when invoked.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] With either definition, `addvalue(.foo)` will add the current input's `.foo` field to each element of the array.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Do note that calling `addvalue(.[])` will cause the `map(. + $f)` part to be evaluated once per value in the value of `.` at the call site.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Multiple definitions using the same function name are allowed.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Each re-definition replaces the previous one for the same number of function arguments, but only for references from functions (or main program) subsequent to the re-definition.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] There are two types of symbols in jq: value bindings (a.k.a., "variables"), and functions.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Both are scoped lexically, with expressions being able to refer only to symbols that have been defined "to the left" of them.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The only exception to this rule is that functions can refer to themselves so as to be able to create recursive functions.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] For example, in the following expression there is a binding which is visible "to the right" of it, `... | .*3 as $times_three | [. + $times_three] | ...`, but not "to the left".
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Consider this expression now, `... | (.*3 as $times_three | [. + $times_three]) | ...`: here the binding `$times_three` is *not* visible past the closing parenthesis.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Returns true if `exp` produces no outputs, false otherwise.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The `limit` function extracts up to `n` outputs from `expr`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The `first(expr)` and `last(expr)` functions extract the first and last values from `expr`, respectively.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The `nth(n; expr)` function extracts the nth value output by `expr`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Note that `nth(n; expr)` doesn't support negative values of `n`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The `first` and `last` functions extract the first and last values from any array at `.`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The `nth(n)` function extracts the nth value of any array at `.`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The `reduce` syntax allows you to combine all of the results of an expression by accumulating them into a single answer.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The form is `reduce EXP as $var (INIT; UPDATE)`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] For each result that `.[]` produces, `. + $item` is run to accumulate a running total, starting from 0 as the input value.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The `foreach` syntax is similar to `reduce`, but intended to allow the construction of `limit` and reducers that produce intermediate results.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The form is `foreach EXP as $var (INIT; UPDATE; EXTRACT)`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Like the `reduce` syntax, `. + $item` is run for each result that `.[]` produces, but `[$item, .
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] * 2]` is run for each intermediate values.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] When `EXTRACT` is omitted, the identity filter is used.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] That is, it outputs the intermediate values as they are.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] As described above, `recurse` uses recursion, and any jq function can be recursive.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The `while` builtin is also implemented in terms of recursion.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Tail calls are optimized whenever the expression to the left of the recursive call outputs its last value.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] In practice this means that the expression to the left of the recursive call should not produce more than one output for each input.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Some jq operators and functions are actually generators in that they can produce zero, one, or more values for each input, just as one might expect in other programming languages that have generators.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] For example, `.[]` generates all the values in its input (which must be an array or an object), `range(0; 10)` generates the integers between 0 and 10, and so on.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Even the comma operator is a generator, generating first the values generated by the expression to the left of the comma, then the values generated by the expression on the right of the comma.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The `empty` builtin is the generator that produces zero outputs.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The `empty` builtin backtracks to the preceding generator expression.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] All jq functions can be generators just by using builtin generators.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] It is also possible to construct new generators using only recursion and the comma operator.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] If recursive calls are "in tail position" then the generator will be efficient.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] In the example below the recursive call by `_range` to itself is in tail position.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The example shows off three advanced topics: tail recursion, generator construction, and sub-functions.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] jq currently only has IEEE754 double-precision (64-bit) floating point number support.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Besides simple arithmetic operators such as `+`, jq also has most standard math functions from the C math library.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] C math functions that take a single input argument (e.g., `sin()`) are available as zero-argument jq functions.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] C math functions that take two input arguments (e.g., `pow()`) are available as two-argument jq functions that ignore `.`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] C math functions that take three input arguments are available as three-argument jq functions that ignore `.`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Availability of standard math functions depends on the availability of the corresponding math functions in your operating system and C math library.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Unavailable math functions will be defined but will raise an error.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Two-input C math functions: `atan2` `copysign` `drem` `fdim` `fmax` `fmin` `fmod` `frexp` `hypot` `jn` `ldexp` `modf` `nextafter` `nexttoward` `pow` `remainder` `scalb` `scalbln` `yn`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] See your system's manual for more information on each of these.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] At this time jq has minimal support for I/O, mostly in the form of control over when inputs are read.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Two builtins functions are provided for this, `input` and `inputs`, that read from the same sources (e.g., `stdin`, files named on the command-line) as jq itself.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] These two builtins, and jq's own reading actions, can be interleaved with each other.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] They are commonly used in combination with the null input option `-n` to prevent one input from being read implicitly.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Two builtins provide minimal output capabilities, `debug`, and `stderr`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] (Recall that a jq program's output values are always output as JSON texts on `stdout`.) The `debug` builtin can have application-specific behavior, such as for executables that use the libjq C API but aren't the jq executable itself.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The `stderr` builtin outputs its input in raw mode to stderr with no additional decoration, not even a newline.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Most jq builtins are referentially transparent, and yield constant and repeatable value streams when applied to constant inputs.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Note that when using `input` it is generally necessary to invoke jq with the `-n` command-line option, otherwise the first entity will be lost.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Outputs all remaining inputs, one by one.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] This is primarily useful for reductions over a program's inputs.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Note that when using `inputs` it is generally necessary to invoke jq with the `-n` command-line option, otherwise the first entity will be lost.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] These two filters are like `.` but have as a side-effect the production of one or more messages on stderr.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] where `<input-value>` is a compact rendition of the input value.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The `debug(msgs)` filter is defined as `(msgs | debug | empty), .` thus allowing great flexibility in the content of the message, while also allowing multi-line debugging statements to be created.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Prints its input in raw and compact mode to stderr with no additional decoration, not even a newline.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Returns the name of the file whose input is currently being filtered.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Note that this will not work well unless jq is running in a UTF-8 locale.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Returns the line number of the input currently being filtered.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] With the `--stream` option jq can parse input texts in a streaming fashion, allowing jq programs to start processing large JSON texts immediately rather than after the parse completes.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] If you have a single JSON text that is 1GB in size, streaming it will allow you to process it much more quickly.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] However, streaming isn't easy to deal with as the jq program will have `[<path>, <leaf-value>]` (and a few other forms) as inputs.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Several builtins are provided to make handling streams easier.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Streaming forms include `[<path>, <leaf-value>]` (to indicate any scalar value, empty array, or empty object), and `[<path>]` (to indicate the end of an array or object).
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Future versions of jq run with `--stream` and `--seq` may output additional forms such as `["error message"]` when an input text fails to parse.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Consumes a number as input and truncates the corresponding number of path elements from the left of the outputs of the given streaming expression.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Outputs values corresponding to the stream expression's outputs.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The `tostream` builtin outputs the streamed form of its input.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Assignment works a little differently in jq than in most programming languages. jq doesn't distinguish between references to and copies of something - two objects or arrays are either equal or not equal, without any further notion of being "the same object" or "not the same object".
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] If an object has two fields which are arrays, `.foo` and `.bar`, and you append something to `.foo`, then `.bar` will not get bigger, even if you've previously set `.bar = .foo`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] If you're used to programming in languages like Python, Java, Ruby, JavaScript, etc. then you can think of it as though jq does a full deep copy of every object before it does the assignment (for performance it doesn't actually do that, but that's the general idea).
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] This means that it's impossible to build circular values in jq (such as an array whose first element is itself).
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] This is quite intentional, and ensures that anything a jq program can produce can be represented in JSON.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] All the assignment operators in jq have path expressions on the left-hand side (LHS).
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The right-hand side (RHS) provides values to set to the paths named by the LHS path expressions.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Internally, assignment works by using a reduction to compute new, replacement values for `.` that have had all the desired assignments applied to `.`, then outputting the modified value.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] This will output `{"a":{"b":3}}` and `{"a":{"b":{"c":1}}}` because the last sub-expression, `.`, sees the original value, not the modified value.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Most users will want to use modification assignment operators, such as `|=` or `+=`, rather than `=`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Note that the LHS of assignment operators refers to a value in `.`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Thus `$var.foo = 1` won't work as expected (`$var.foo` is not a valid or useful path expression in `.`); use `$var | .foo = 1` instead.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] It takes a filter on the right-hand side and works out the new value for the property of `.` being assigned to by running the old value through this expression.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] For instance, `(.foo, .bar) |= .+1` will build an object with the `foo` field set to the input's `foo` plus 1, and the `bar` field set to the input's `bar` plus 1.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The left-hand side can be any general path expression; see `path()`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Note that the left-hand side of `|=` refers to a value in `.`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Thus `$var.foo |= . + 1` won't work as expected (`$var.foo` is not a valid or useful path expression in `.`); use `$var | .foo |= . + 1` instead.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] If the right-hand side outputs no values (i.e., `empty`), then the left-hand side path will be deleted, as with `del(path)`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] If the right-hand side outputs multiple values, only the first one will be used (COMPATIBILITY NOTE: in jq 1.5 and earlier releases, it used to be that only the last one was used).
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] jq has a few operators of the form `a op= b`, which are all equivalent to `a |= . op b`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] So, `+= 1` can be used to increment values, being the same as `|= . + 1`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Unlike the others, the input to the right-hand side (RHS) is the same as the input to the left-hand side (LHS) rather than the value at the LHS path, and all values output by the RHS will be used (as shown below).
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] If the RHS of `=` produces multiple values, then for each such value jq will set the paths on the left-hand side to the value and then it will output the modified `.`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The "update" assignment forms (see above) do not do this.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The former will set the `a` field of the input to the `b` field of the input, and produce the output `{"a": 20, "b": 20}`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] The latter will set the `a` field of the input to the `a` field's `b` field, producing `{"a": 10, "b": 20}`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Lots more things are allowed on the left-hand side of a jq assignment than in most languages.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] That example appends the string "this is great" to the "comments" array of each post in the input (where the input is an object with a field "posts" which is an array of posts).
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] When jq encounters an assignment like 'a = b', it records the "path" taken to select a part of the input document while executing a.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] This path is then used to find which part of the input to change while executing the assignment.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Any filter may be used on the left-hand side of an equals - whichever paths it selects from the input will be where the assignment is performed.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] Suppose we wanted to add a comment to blog posts, using the same "blog" input above.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p03] This time, we only want to comment on the posts written by "stedolan".
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p04] Modules are files whose names end in `.jq`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p04] Modules imported by a program are searched for in a default search path (see below).
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p04] The `import` and `include` directives allow the importer to alter this path.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p04] Paths in the search path are subject to various substitutions.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p04] For paths starting with `~/`, the user's home directory is substituted for `~`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p04] For paths starting with `$ORIGIN/`, the directory where the jq executable is located is substituted for `$ORIGIN`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p04] For paths starting with `./` or paths that are `.`, the path of the including file is substituted for `.`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p04] For top-level programs given on the command-line, the current directory is used.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p04] Import directives can optionally specify a search path to which the default is appended.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p04] The default search path is the search path given to the `-L` command-line option, else `["~/.jq", "$ORIGIN/../lib/jq", "$ORIGIN/../lib"]`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p04] Null and empty string path elements terminate search path processing.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p04] A dependency with relative path `foo/bar` would be searched for in `foo/bar.jq` and `foo/bar/bar.jq` in the given search path.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p04] This is intended to allow modules to be placed in a directory along with, for example, version control files, README files, and so on, but also to allow for single-file modules.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p04] Consecutive components with the same name are not allowed to avoid ambiguities (e.g., `foo/foo`).
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p04] For example, with `-L$HOME/.jq` a module `foo` can be found in `$HOME/.jq/foo.jq` and `$HOME/.jq/foo/foo.jq`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p04] If `.jq` exists in the user's home directory, and is a file (not a directory), it is automatically sourced into the main program.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p04] Imports a module found at the given path relative to a directory in a search path.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p04] A `.jq` suffix will be added to the relative path string.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p04] The module's symbols are prefixed with `NAME::`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p04] The optional metadata must be a constant jq expression.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p04] It should be an object with keys like `homepage` and so on.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p04] At this time jq only uses the `search` key/value of the metadata.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p04] The metadata is also made available to users via the `modulemeta` builtin.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p04] The `search` key in the metadata, if present, should have a string or array value (array of strings); this is the search path to be prefixed to the top-level search path.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p04] Imports a module found at the given path relative to a directory in a search path as if it were included in place.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p04] The module's symbols are imported into the caller's namespace as if the module's content had been included directly.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p04] Imports a JSON file found at the given path relative to a directory in a search path.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p04] A `.json` suffix will be added to the relative path string.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p04] The file's data will be available as `$NAME::NAME`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p04] It serves only the purpose of providing metadata that can be read with the `modulemeta` builtin.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p04] The metadata must be a constant jq expression.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p04] It should be an object with keys like `homepage`.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p04] At this time jq doesn't use this metadata, but it is made available to users via the `modulemeta` builtin.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p04] Takes a module name as input and outputs the module's metadata as an object, with the module's imports (including metadata) as an array value for the `deps` key and the module's defined functions as an array value for the `defs` key.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p04] Programs can use this to query a module's metadata, which they could then use to, for example, search for, download, and install missing dependencies.
[src:jq-json/jq-manual-p04] This is not a manual for VT100/ANSI escapes.
[src:jq-json/jq-programming-language] jq was created by Stephen Dolan, and released in October 2012.
[src:jq-json/jq-programming-language] It was described as being "like sed for JSON data".
[src:jq-json/jq-programming-language] Support for regular expressions was added in jq version 1.5.
[src:jq-json/jq-programming-language] The original implementation of jq was in Haskell before being ported to the language C.
[src:jq-json/jq-programming-language] jq is typically used at the command line and can be used with other command-line utilities, such as GNU Wget.
[src:jq-json/jq-programming-language] The `wget` command above uses the MediaWiki API for this page to produce a JSON response.
[src:jq-json/jq-programming-language] The pipe `|` allows the output of `wget` to be accessed by jq, a standard Unix shell mechanism.
[src:jq-json/jq-programming-language] This corresponds to the nested JSON structure produced by the call to `wget`.
[src:jq-json/jq-programming-language] Notice that the jq pipeline is constructed in the same manner using the `|` character as the Unix-style pipeline.
[src:jq-json/jq-programming-language] jq provides a C API, libjq, allowing it to be used from C.
[src:jq-json/jq-programming-language] jq by default acts as a "stream editor" for JSON inputs, much like the sed utility can be thought of as a "stream editor" for lines of text.
[src:jq-json/jq-programming-language] 3. it can parse its JSON inputs using a so-called "streaming parser" that produces a stream of [path, value] arrays for all "leaf" paths.
[src:jq-json/jq-programming-language] The *streaming parser* is very useful when one of more of the JSON inputs is too large to fit in memory, since its memory needs are usually quite small.
[src:jq-json/jq-programming-language] For example, for an arbitrarily large array of JSON objects, the peak memory need is little more than needed to handle the largest top-level object.
[src:jq-json/jq-programming-language] These modes of operation can, within certain limitations, be combined.
[src:jq-json/jq-programming-language] Every JSON value is also a value in jq, which accordingly has the data types shown in the table below.
[src:jq-json/jq-programming-language] `null` is a value, just like any other JSON scalar; it is not a pointer or a "null pointer".
[src:jq-json/jq-programming-language] `nan` (corresponding to NaN) and `infinite` (see IEEE 754) are the only two jq scalars that are not also JSON values.
[src:jq-json/jq-programming-language] Special syntactic forms exist for function creation, conditionals, stream reduction, and the module system.
[src:jq-json/jq-programming-language] Here is an example of defining a named, parameterized filter for formatting an integer in any base from 2 to 36 inclusive.
[src:jq-json/jq-programming-language] jq has inspired several clones and similar programs.
[src:jq-json/jq-programming-language] jaq is a Rust implementation of jq developed using denotational semantics to formalize its behavior in cases where the original jq documentation is unclear or does not match its behavior.
[src:jq-json/jq-programming-language] Mike Farah's yq is a jq-like program that supports several file formats, including JSON, YAML, and XML.
[src:jq-json/jq-programming-language] Its syntax is not fully compatible with jq.
[src:jq-json/jq-programming-language] Andrey Kislyuk's yq provides a collection of wrapper scripts that use jq to process YAML, XML, or TOML files.
[src:jq-json/jq-tutorial] GitHub has a JSON API, so let's play with that.
[src:jq-json/jq-tutorial] This URL gets us the last 5 commits from the jq repo.
[src:jq-json/jq-tutorial] For servers that don't, it can be helpful to pipe the response through jq to pretty-print it.
[src:jq-json/jq-tutorial] The simplest jq program is the expression `.`, which takes the input and produces it unchanged as output.
[src:jq-json/jq-tutorial] We can use jq to extract just the first commit.
[src:jq-json/jq-tutorial] For the rest of the examples, I'll leave out the `curl` command - it's not going to change.
[src:jq-json/jq-tutorial] There's a lot of info we don't care about there, so we'll restrict it down to the most interesting fields.
[src:jq-json/jq-tutorial] The `|` operator in jq feeds the output of one filter (`.[0]` which gets the first element of the array in the response) into the input of another (`{...}` which builds an object out of those fields).
[src:jq-json/jq-tutorial] You can access nested attributes, such as `.commit.message`.
[src:jq-json/jq-tutorial] `.[]` returns each element of the array returned in the response, one at a time, which are all fed into `{message: .commit.message, name: .commit.committer.name}`.
[src:jq-json/jq-tutorial] Data in jq is represented as streams of JSON values - every jq expression runs for each value in its input stream, and can produce any number of values to its output stream.
[src:jq-json/jq-tutorial] Streams are serialised by just separating JSON values with whitespace.
[src:jq-json/jq-tutorial] This is a `cat`-friendly format - you can just join two JSON streams together and get a valid JSON stream.
[src:jq-json/jq-tutorial] Next, let's try getting the URLs of the parent commits out of the API results as well.
[src:jq-json/jq-tutorial] In each commit, the GitHub API includes information about "parent" commits.
[src:jq-json/jq-tutorial] We want to pull out all of the "html_url" fields inside that array of parent commits and make a simple list of strings to go along with the "message" and "author" fields we already have.
[src:jq-json/jq-tutorial] Here we're making an object as before, but this time the `parents` field is being set to `[.parents[].html_url]`, which collects all of the parent commit URLs defined in the parents object.
[src:jq-json/jq-tutorial] Go read the manual if you're interested, and download jq if you haven't already.
[src:jq-json/json-streaming] JSON is a popular format for exchanging object data between systems.
[src:jq-json/json-streaming] Frequently there's a need for a stream of objects to be sent over a single connection, such as a stock ticker or application log records.
[src:jq-json/json-streaming] In these cases there's a need to identify where one JSON encoded object ends and the next begins.
[src:jq-json/json-streaming] Line-delimited JSON works very well with traditional line-oriented tools.
[src:jq-json/json-streaming] Concatenated JSON works with pretty-printed JSON but requires more effort and complexity to parse.
[src:jq-json/json-streaming] It doesn't work well with traditional line-oriented tools.
[src:jq-json/json-streaming] Concatenated JSON streaming is a superset of line-delimited JSON streaming.
[src:jq-json/json-streaming] Length-prefixed JSON works with pretty-printed JSON.
[src:jq-json/json-streaming] It doesn't work well with traditional line-oriented tools, but may offer performance advantages over line-delimited or concatenated streaming.
[src:jq-json/json-streaming] Streaming makes use of the fact that the JSON format does not allow return and newline characters within primitive values (in strings those must be escaped as `\r` and `\n`, respectively) and that most JSON formatters default to not including any whitespace, including returns and newlines.
[src:jq-json/json-streaming] These features allow the newline character or return and newline character sequence to be used as a delimiter.
[src:jq-json/json-streaming] The use of a newline as a delimiter enables this format to work very well with traditional line-oriented Unix tools.
[src:jq-json/json-streaming] which is very easy to sort by date, grep for usernames, actions, IP addresses, etc.
[src:jq-json/json-streaming] Line-delimited JSON can be read by a parser that can handle concatenated JSON.
[src:jq-json/json-streaming] Concatenated JSON that contains newlines *within* a JSON object can't be read by a line-delimited JSON parser.
[src:jq-json/json-streaming] The terms "line-delimited JSON" and "newline-delimited JSON" are often used without clarifying if embedded newlines are supported.
[src:jq-json/json-streaming] In the past the newline delimited JSON specification allowed comments to be embedded if the first two characters of a given line were "//".
[src:jq-json/json-streaming] This could not be used with standard JSON parsers if comments were included.
[src:jq-json/json-streaming] Current version of the specification ("NDJSON - Newline delimited JSON ") no longer includes comments.
[src:jq-json/json-streaming] Concatenated JSON can be converted into line-delimited JSON by a suitable JSON utility such as jq.
[src:jq-json/json-streaming] Record separator-delimited JSON streaming allows JSON text sequences to be delimited without the requirement that the JSON formatter exclude whitespace.
[src:jq-json/json-streaming] Since JSON text sequences cannot contain control characters, a record separator character can be used to delimit the sequences.
[src:jq-json/json-streaming] In addition, it is suggested that each JSON text sequence be followed by a line feed character to allow proper handling of top-level JSON objects that are not self delimiting (numbers, true, false, and null).
[src:jq-json/json-streaming] This format is also known as JSON Text Sequences or MIME type `application/json-seq`, and is formally described in IETF RFC 7464.
[src:jq-json/json-streaming] Concatenated JSON streaming allows the sender to simply write each JSON object into the stream with no delimiters.
[src:jq-json/json-streaming] It relies on the receiver using a parser that can recognize and *emit* each JSON object as the terminating character is parsed.
[src:jq-json/json-streaming] Concatenated JSON isn't a new format, it's simply a name for streaming multiple JSON objects without any delimiters.
[src:jq-json/json-streaming] The advantage of this format is that it can handle JSON objects that have been formatted with embedded newline characters, e.g., pretty-printed for human readability.
[src:jq-json/json-streaming] Implementations that rely on line-based input may require a newline character after each JSON object in order for the object to be emitted by the parser in a timely manner.
[src:jq-json/json-streaming] (Otherwise the line may remain in the input buffer without being passed to the parser.) This is rarely recognised as an issue because terminating JSON objects with a newline character is very common.
[src:jq-json/json-streaming] Length-prefixed or framed JSON streaming allows the sender to explicitly state the length of each message.
[src:jq-json/json-streaming] It relies on the receiver using a parser that can recognize each length *n* and then read the following *n* bytes to parse as JSON.
[src:jq-json/json-streaming] The advantage of this format is that it can speed up parsing due to the fact that the exact length of each message is explicitly stated, rather than forcing the parser to search for delimiters.
[src:jq-json/json-streaming] Length-prefixed JSON is also well-suited for TCP applications, where a single "message" may be divided into arbitrary chunks, because the prefixed length tells the parser exactly how many bytes to expect before attempting to parse a JSON string.
[src:jq-json/json] JSON is a programming language-independent data format.
[src:jq-json/json] It was derived from JavaScript, but many modern programming languages include code to generate and parse JSON-format data.
[src:jq-json/json] JSON filenames use the extension `.json`.
[src:jq-json/json] Douglas Crockford originally specified the JSON format in the early 2000s.
[src:jq-json/json] They and Chip Morningstar sent the first JSON message in April 2001.
[src:jq-json/json] The 2017 international standard (ECMA-404 and ISO/IEC 21778:2017) specifies that "JSON" is "pronounced /ˈdʒeɪ.sən/, as in 'Jason and The Argonauts'".
[src:jq-json/json] The first (2013) edition of ECMA-404 did not address the pronunciation.
[src:jq-json/json] Crockford said in 2011, "There's a lot of argument about how you pronounce that, but I strictly don't care." /ˈdʒeɪˌsɒn/ is another common pronunciation.
[src:jq-json/json] After RFC 4627 had been available as its "informational" specification since 2006, JSON was first standardized in 2013, as ECMA-404.
[src:jq-json/json] RFC 8259, published in 2017, is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90, and it remains consistent with ECMA-404.
[src:jq-json/json] That same year, JSON was also standardized as ISO/IEC 21778:2017.
[src:jq-json/json] The ECMA and ISO/IEC standards describe only the allowed syntax, whereas the RFC covers some security and interoperability considerations.
[src:jq-json/json] JSON grew out of a need for a real-time server-to-browser session communication protocol without using browser plugins such as Flash or Java applets, the dominant methods used in the early 2000s.
[src:jq-json/json] Crockford first specified and popularized the JSON format.
[src:jq-json/json] The acronym originated at State Software, a company cofounded by Crockford and others in March 2001.
[src:jq-json/json] The cofounders had a round-table discussion and voted on whether to call the data format JSML (JavaScript Markup Language) or JSON (JavaScript Object Notation), as well as under what license type to make it available.
[src:jq-json/json] The JSON.org website was launched in 2001.
[src:jq-json/json] In December 2005, Yahoo! began offering some of its Web services in JSON.
[src:jq-json/json] A precursor to the JSON libraries was used in a children's digital asset trading game project named Cartoon Orbit at Communities.com which used a browser side plug-in with a proprietary messaging format to manipulate DHTML elements.
[src:jq-json/json] Crockford then found that JavaScript could be used as an object-based messaging format for such a system.
[src:jq-json/json] The system was sold to Sun Microsystems, Amazon.com, and EDS.
[src:jq-json/json] JSON was based on a subset of the JavaScript scripting language (specifically, Standard ECMA-262 3rd Edition—December 1999) and is commonly used with JavaScript, but it is a language-independent data format.
[src:jq-json/json] Code for parsing and generating JSON data is readily available in many programming languages.
[src:jq-json/json] JSON's website lists JSON libraries by language.
[src:jq-json/json] In October 2013, Ecma International published the first edition of its JSON standard ECMA-404.
[src:jq-json/json] That same year, RFC 7158 used ECMA-404 as a reference.
[src:jq-json/json] In 2014, RFC 7159 became the main reference for JSON's Internet uses, superseding RFC 4627 and RFC 7158 (but preserving ECMA-262 and ECMA-404 as main references).
[src:jq-json/json] In November 2017, ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 22 published ISO/IEC 21778:2017 as an international standard.
[src:jq-json/json] On December 13, 2017, the Internet Engineering Task Force obsoleted RFC 7159 when it published RFC 8259, which is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90.
[src:jq-json/json] Crockford added a clause to the JSON license stating, "The Software shall be used for Good, not Evil", in order to open-source the JSON libraries while mocking corporate lawyers and those who are overly pedantic.
[src:jq-json/json] On the other hand, this clause led to license compatibility problems of the JSON license with other open-source licenses since open-source software and free software usually imply no restrictions on the purpose of use.
[src:jq-json/json] The following example shows a possible JSON representation describing a person.
[src:jq-json/json] This is a consequence of JSON disallowing only "control characters".
[src:jq-json/json] For maximum portability, these characters are backslash-escaped.
[src:jq-json/json] JSON exchange in an open ecosystem must be encoded in UTF-8.
[src:jq-json/json] The encoding supports the full Unicode character set, including those characters outside the Basic Multilingual Plane (U+0000 to U+FFFF).
[src:jq-json/json] However, if escaped, those characters must be written using UTF-16 surrogate pairs.
[src:jq-json/json] JSON became a strict subset of ECMAScript as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:jq-json/json] Whitespace is allowed and ignored around or between syntactic elements (values and punctuation, but not within a string value).
[src:jq-json/json] Four specific characters are considered whitespace for this purpose: space, horizontal tab, line feed, and carriage return.
[src:jq-json/json] In particular, the byte order mark must not be generated by a conforming implementation (though it may be accepted when parsing JSON).
[src:jq-json/json] JSON does not provide syntax for comments.
[src:jq-json/json] Early versions of JSON (such as specified by RFC 4627) required that a valid JSON text must consist of only an object or an array type, which could contain other types within them.
[src:jq-json/json] This restriction was dropped in RFC 7158, where a JSON text was redefined as any serialized value.
[src:jq-json/json] Numbers in JSON are agnostic with regard to their representation within programming languages.
[src:jq-json/json] While this allows for numbers of arbitrary precision to be serialized, it may lead to portability issues.
[src:jq-json/json] For example, since no differentiation is made between integer and floating-point values, some implementations may treat `42`, `42.0`, and `4.2E+1` as the same number, while others may not.
[src:jq-json/json] The JSON standard makes no requirements regarding implementation details such as overflow, underflow, loss of precision, rounding, or signed zeros, but it does recommend expecting no more than IEEE 754 binary64 precision for "good interoperability".
[src:jq-json/json] There is no inherent precision loss in serializing a machine-level binary representation of a floating-point number (like binary64) into a human-readable decimal representation (like numbers in JSON) and back; there exist published algorithms to do this conversion exactly and optimally.
[src:jq-json/json] Comments were intentionally excluded from JSON.
[src:jq-json/json] JSON disallows "trailing commas", a comma after the last value inside a data structure.
[src:jq-json/json] Trailing commas are a common feature of JSON derivatives to improve ease of use.
[src:jq-json/json] RFC 8259 describes certain aspects of JSON syntax that, while legal per the specifications, can cause interoperability problems.
[src:jq-json/json] In 2015, the IETF published RFC 7493, describing the "I-JSON Message Format", a restricted profile of JSON that constrains the syntax and processing of JSON to avoid, as much as possible, these interoperability issues.
[src:jq-json/json] While JSON provides a syntactic framework for data interchange, unambiguous data interchange also requires agreement between producer and consumer on the semantics of specific use of the JSON syntax.
[src:jq-json/json] One example of where such an agreement is necessary is the serialization of data types that are not part of the JSON standard, for example, dates and regular expressions.
[src:jq-json/json] The official MIME type for JSON text is `application/json`, and most modern implementations have adopted this.
[src:jq-json/json] Legacy MIME types include `text/json`, `text/x-json`, and `text/javascript`.
[src:jq-json/json] The standard filename extension is .json.
[src:jq-json/json] The JSON standard does not support object references, but an IETF draft standard for JSON-based object references exists.
[src:jq-json/json] JSON-RPC is a remote procedure call (RPC) protocol built on JSON, as a replacement for XML-RPC or SOAP.
[src:jq-json/json] It is a simple protocol that defines only a handful of data types and commands.
[src:jq-json/json] JSON-RPC lets a system send notifications (information to the server that does not require a response) and multiple calls to the server that can be answered out of order.
[src:jq-json/json] Asynchronous JavaScript and JSON (or AJAJ) refers to the same dynamic web page methodology as Ajax, but instead of XML, JSON is the data format.
[src:jq-json/json] AJAJ is a web development technique that provides for the ability of a web page to request new data after it has loaded into the web browser.
[src:jq-json/json] Typically, it renders new data from the server in response to user actions on that web page.
[src:jq-json/json] For example, what the user types into a search box, client-side code then sends to the server, which immediately responds with a drop-down list of matching database items.
[src:jq-json/json] JSON has seen ad hoc usage as a configuration language.
[src:jq-json/json] In 2012, Douglas Crockford, JSON creator, had this to say about comments in JSON when used as a configuration language: "I know that the lack of comments makes some people sad, but it shouldn't.
[src:jq-json/json] Suppose you are using JSON to keep configuration files, which you would like to annotate.
[src:jq-json/json] Go ahead and insert all the comments you like.
[src:jq-json/json] MongoDB uses JSON-like data for its document-oriented database.
[src:jq-json/json] Some relational databases have added support for native JSON data types, such as JSONB in PostgreSQL and JSON in MySQL.
[src:jq-json/json] This allows developers to insert JSON data directly without having to convert it to another format.
[src:jq-json/json] JSON being a subset of JavaScript can lead to the misconception that it is safe to pass JSON texts to the JavaScript `eval()` function.
[src:jq-json/json] This is not safe, due to certain valid JSON texts, specifically those containing U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR or U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR, not being valid JavaScript code until JavaScript specifications were updated in 2019, and so older engines may not support it.
[src:jq-json/json] To avoid the many pitfalls caused by executing arbitrary code from the Internet, a new function, `JSON.parse()`, was first added to the fifth edition of ECMAScript, which as of 2017 is supported by all major browsers.
[src:jq-json/json] For non-supported browsers, an API-compatible JavaScript library is provided by Douglas Crockford.
[src:jq-json/json] In addition, the TC39 proposal "Subsume JSON" made ECMAScript a strict JSON superset as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:jq-json/json] Various JSON parser implementations have suffered from denial-of-service attack and mass assignment vulnerability.
[src:jq-json/json] JSON is promoted as a low-overhead alternative to XML as both of these formats have widespread support for creation, reading, and decoding in the real-world situations where they are commonly used.
[src:jq-json/json] XML has been used to describe structured data and to serialize objects.
[src:jq-json/json] Various XML-based protocols exist to represent the same kind of data structures as JSON for the same kind of data interchange purposes.
[src:jq-json/json] Data can be encoded in XML in several ways.
[src:jq-json/json] The most expansive form using tag pairs results in a much larger (in character count) representation than JSON, but if data is stored in attributes and *short tag* form where the closing tag is replaced with `/>`, the representation is often about the same size as JSON or just a little larger.
[src:jq-json/json] However, an XML attribute can only have a single value and each attribute can appear at most once on each element.
[src:jq-json/json] XML separates data from metadata (via the use of elements and attributes), while JSON does not have such a concept.
[src:jq-json/json] Another key difference is the addressing of values.
[src:jq-json/json] JSON has objects with a simple key-to-value mapping, whereas in XML addressing happens on *nodes*, each of which receives a unique ID via the XML processor.
[src:jq-json/json] Additionally, the XML standard defines a common attribute `xml:id`, that can be used by the user, to set an ID explicitly.
[src:jq-json/json] XML tag names cannot contain any of the characters !"#$%&'()*+,/;<=>?@[\]^`{|}~, nor a space character, and cannot begin with `-`, `.`, or a numeric digit, whereas JSON keys can (even if quotation mark and backslash must be escaped).
[src:jq-json/json] XML values are strings of *characters*, with no built-in type safety.
[src:jq-json/json] XML has the concept of schema, that permits strong typing, user-defined types, predefined tags, and formal structure, allowing for formal validation of an XML stream.
[src:jq-json/json] JSON has several types built-in and has a similar schema concept in JSON Schema.
[src:jq-json/json] XML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:jq-json/json] Support for comments and other features have been deemed useful, which has led to several nonstandard JSON supersets being created.
[src:jq-json/json] Among them are HJSON, HOCON, and JSON5 (which despite its name, is not the fifth version of JSON).
[src:jq-json/json] YAML version 1.2 is a superset of JSON; prior versions were not strictly compatible.
[src:jq-json/json] For example, escaping a slash `/` with a backslash `\` is valid in JSON, but was not valid in YAML.
[src:jq-json/json] YAML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:jq-json/json] There is also an unrelated project called **CSON** ("Cursive Script Object Notation") that is more syntactically similar to JSON.
[src:jq-json/json] JSON5 syntax is supported in some software as an extension of JSON syntax, for instance in SQLite.
[src:jq-json/json] Several serialization formats have been built on or from the JSON specification.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The *options* are described in the [INVOKING JQ] section; they mostly concern input and output formatting.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The *filter* is written in the jq language and specifies how to transform the input file or document.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] Some filters produce multiple results, for instance there´s one that produces all the elements of its input array.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] It´s important to remember that every filter has an input and an output.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] So, you can implement an averaging filter as **add / length** - feeding the input array both to the **add** filter and the **length** filter and then performing the division.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The simplest and most common filter (or jq program) is **.**, which is the identity operator, copying the inputs of the jq processor to the output stream.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] Because the default behavior of the jq processor is to read JSON texts from the input stream, and to pretty-print outputs, the **.** program´s main use is to validate and pretty-print the inputs.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] Note: it is important to mind the shell´s quoting rules.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] As a general rule it´s best to always quote (with single-quote characters on Unix shells) the jq program, as too many characters with special meaning to jq are also shell meta-characters.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] For example, **jq "foo"** will fail on most Unix shells because that will be the same as **jq foo**, which will generally fail because **foo is not defined**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] When using the Windows command shell (cmd.exe) it´s best to use double quotes around your jq program when given on the command-line (instead of the **-f program-file** option), but then double-quotes in the jq program need backslash escaping.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] When using the Powershell (**powershell.exe**) or the Powershell Core (**pwsh**/**pwsh.exe**), use single-quote characters around the jq program and backslash-escaped double-quotes (**\"**) inside the jq program.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] , then the entire input is passed to the filter as a single long string.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] With this option, if the filter´s result is a string then it will be written directly to standard output rather than being formatted as a JSON string with quotes.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] but jq will print NUL instead of newline after each output.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] but jq won´t print a newline after each output.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] Flush the output after each JSON object is printed (useful if you´re piping a slow data source into jq and piping jq´s output elsewhere).
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] syntax to reduce large inputs incrementally.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] , but invalid JSON inputs yield array values where the first element is the error and the second is a path.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] MIME type scheme for separating JSON texts in jq´s input and output.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] Read the filter from a file rather than from a command line, like awk´s -f option.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] , or 4 if no valid result was ever produced.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] , then a line containing the program to compile, then a line containing an error message to compare to the actual.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] Since jq by default pretty-prints all output, a trivial program consisting of nothing but **.** can be used to format JSON output from, say, **curl**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] (2) jq will attempt to maintain the original decimal precision of number literals (if the **--disable-decnum** build configuration option was not used), but in expressions such **1E1234567890**, precision will be lost if the exponent is too large.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The examples below use the builtin function **have_decnum** in order to demonstrate the expected effects of using / not using the **--disable-decnum** build configuration option, and also to allow automated tests derived from these examples to pass regardless of whether that option is used.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The simplest *useful* filter has the form **.foo**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] When given a JSON object (aka dictionary or hash) as input, **.foo** produces the value at the key "foo" if the key is present, or null otherwise.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] A filter of the form **.foo.bar** is equivalent to **.foo | .bar**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The **.foo** syntax only works for simple, identifier-like keys, that is, keys that are all made of alphanumeric characters and underscore, and which do not start with a digit.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] If the key contains special characters or starts with a digit, you need to surround it with double quotes like this: **."foo$"**, or else **.["foo$"]**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] Just like **.foo**, but does not output an error when **.** is not an object.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] You can also look up fields of an object using syntax like **.["foo"]** (**.foo** above is a shorthand version of this, but only for identifier-like strings).
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] When the index value is an integer, **.[<number>]** can index arrays.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] Arrays are zero-based, so **.[2]** returns the third element.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The **.[<number>:<number>]** syntax can be used to return a subarray of an array or substring of a string.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The array returned by **.[10:15]** will be of length 5, containing the elements from index 10 (inclusive) to index 15 (exclusive).
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] If you use the **.[index]** syntax, but omit the index entirely, it will return *all* of the elements of an array.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] Running **.[]** with the input **[1,2,3]** will produce the numbers as three separate results, rather than as a single array.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] A filter of the form **.foo[]** is equivalent to **.foo | .[]**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] Like **.[]**, but no errors will be output if . is not an array or object.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] If two filters are separated by a comma, then the same input will be fed into both and the two filters´ output value streams will be concatenated in order: first, all of the outputs produced by the left expression, and then all of the outputs produced by the right.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] For instance, filter **.foo, .bar**, produces both the "foo" fields and "bar" fields as separate outputs.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The **,** operator is one way to construct generators.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] It´s similar to the Unix shell´s pipe, if you´re used to that.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] So, the expression **.[] | .foo** retrieves the "foo" field of each element of the input array.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] Note too that **.** is the input value at the particular stage in a "pipeline", specifically: where the **.** expression appears.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] Thus **.a | . | .b** is the same as **.a.b**, as the **.** in the middle refers to whatever value **.a** produced.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] Just like everything else in jq, these simple values take an input and produce an output - **42** is a valid jq expression that takes an input, ignores it, and returns 42 instead.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] If you have a filter **X** that produces four results, then the expression **[X]** will produce a single result, an array of four elements.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] Like JSON, **{}** is for constructing objects (aka dictionaries or hashes), as in: **{"a": 42, "b": 17}**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] If the keys are "identifier-like", then the quotes can be left off, as in **{a:42, b:17}**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] Key expressions other than constant literals, identifiers, or variable references, need to be parenthesized, e.g., **{("a"+"b"):59}**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The value can be any expression (although you may need to wrap it in parentheses if, for example, it contains colons), which gets applied to the {} expression´s input (remember, all filters have an input and an output).
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] will produce the JSON object **{"foo": 42}** if given the JSON object **{"bar":42, "baz":43}** as its input.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] Because that is so common, there´s a shortcut syntax for it: **{user, title}**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] Recursively descends **.**, producing every value.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] This is the same as the zero-argument **recurse** builtin (see below).
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] This is intended to resemble the XPath **//** operator.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] In the example below we use **.. | .a?** to find all the values of object keys "a" in any object found "below" **.**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] This is particularly useful in conjunction with **path(EXP)** (also see below) and the **?** operator.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] Some jq operators (for instance, **+**) do different things depending on the type of their arguments (arrays, numbers, etc.).
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] If you try to add a string to an object you´ll get an error message and no result.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The operator **+** takes two filters, applies them both to the same input, and adds the results together.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] As well as normal arithmetic subtraction on numbers, the **-** operator can be used on arrays to remove all occurrences of the second array´s elements from the first array.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The builtin function **abs** is defined naively as: **if . < 0 then - . else . end**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] To compute the absolute value of a number as a floating point number, you may wish use **fabs**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The builtin function **utf8bytelength** outputs the number of bytes used to encode a string in UTF-8.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The builtin function **keys**, when given an object, returns its keys in an array.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] When **keys** is given an array, it returns the valid indices for that array: the integers from 0 to length-1.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The **keys_unsorted** function is just like **keys**, but if the input is an object then the keys will not be sorted, instead the keys will roughly be in insertion order.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The builtin function **has** returns whether the input object has the given key, or the input array has an element at the given index.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The builtin function **in** returns whether or not the input key is in the given object, or the input index corresponds to an element in the given array.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] It is, essentially, an inversed version of **has**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] For any filter **f**, **map(f)** and **map_values(f)** apply **f** to each of the values in the input array or object, that is, to the values of **.[]**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] In the absence of errors, **map(f)** always outputs an array whereas **map_values(f)** outputs an array if given an array, or an object if given an object.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] When the input to **map_values(f)** is an object, the output object has the same keys as the input object except for those keys whose values when piped to **f** produce no values at all.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The key difference between **map(f)** and **map_values(f)** is that the former simply forms an array from all the values of **($x|f)** for each value, **$x**, in the input array or object, but **map_values(f)** only uses **first($x|f)**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] Specifically, for object inputs, **map_values(f)** constructs the output object by examining in turn the value of **first(.[$k]|f)** for each key, **$k**, of the input.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] If this expression produces no values, then the corresponding key will be dropped; otherwise, the output object will have that value at the key, **$k**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] Here are some examples to clarify the behavior of **map** and **map_values** when applied to arrays.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] Emit the projection of the input object or array defined by the specified sequence of path expressions, such that if **p** is any one of these specifications, then **(. | p)** will evaluate to the same value as **(. | pick(pathexps) | p)**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] For arrays, negative indices and **.[m:n]** specifications should not be used.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] Outputs array representations of the given path expression in **.**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] Path expressions are jq expressions like **.a**, but also **.[]**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] For example, **.a.b.c** is an exact match path expression, while **.a[].b** is not.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The expression **path(..|select(type=="boolean"))** outputs all the paths to boolean values in **.**, and only those paths.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The builtin function **del** removes a key and its corresponding value from an object.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The builtin function **getpath** outputs the values in **.** found at each path in **PATHS**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The builtin function **setpath** sets the **PATHS** in **.** to **VALUE**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The builtin function **delpaths** deletes the **PATHS** in **.**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] **PATHS** must be an array of paths, where each path is an array of strings and numbers.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] If **to_entries** is passed an object, then for each **k: v** entry in the input, the output array includes **{"key": k, "value": v}**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The function **select(f)** produces its input unchanged if **f** returns true for that input, and produces no output otherwise.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] Stops the jq program with no further outputs. jq will exit with exit status **0**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The input will be printed on **stderr** as raw output (i.e., strings will not have double quotes) with no decoration, not even a newline.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The given **exit_code** (defaulting to **5**) will be jq´s exit status.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] For example, **"Error: something went wrong\n"|halt_error(1)**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] Produces an object with a "file" key and a "line" key, with the filename and line number where **$__loc__** occurs, as values.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The filter **add** takes as input an array, and produces as output the elements of the array added together.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] This might mean summed, concatenated or merged depending on the types of the elements of the input array - the rules are the same as those for the **+** operator (described above).
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] If the input is an empty array, **add** returns **null**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The filter **any** takes as input an array of boolean values, and produces **true** as output if any of the elements of the array are **true**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] If the input is an empty array, **any** returns **false**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The **any(condition)** form applies the given condition to the elements of the input array.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The **any(generator; condition)** form applies the given condition to all the outputs of the given generator.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The filter **all** takes as input an array of boolean values, and produces **true** as output if all of the elements of the array are **true**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The **all(condition)** form applies the given condition to the elements of the input array.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The **all(generator; condition)** form applies the given condition to all the outputs of the given generator.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] If the input is an empty array, **all** returns **true**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The filter **flatten** takes as input an array of nested arrays, and produces a flat array in which all arrays inside the original array have been recursively replaced by their values.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] flatten(2) is like **flatten**, but going only up to two levels deep.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The **range** function produces a range of numbers.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] **range(4; 10)** produces 6 numbers, from 4 (inclusive) to 10 (exclusive).
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] Use **[range(4; 10)]** to get a range as an array.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The two argument form generates numbers from **from** to **upto** with an increment of 1.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The three argument form generates numbers **from** to **upto** with an increment of **by**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The **floor** function returns the floor of its numeric input.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The **sqrt** function returns the square root of its numeric input.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The **tonumber** function parses its input as a number.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The **toboolean** function parses its input as a boolean.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The **tostring** function prints its input as a string.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The **type** function returns the type of its argument as a string, which is one of null, boolean, number, string, array or object.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The **isinfinite** builtin returns **true** if its input is infinite.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The **isnan** builtin returns **true** if its input is a NaN.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The **infinite** builtin returns a positive infinite value.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The **isnormal** builtin returns true if its input is a normal number.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The **sort** functions sorts its input, which must be an array.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The ordering for objects is a little complex: first they´re compared by comparing their sets of keys (as arrays in sorted order), and if their keys are equal then the values are compared key by key.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] Any jq expression, not just a field access, may be used in place of **.foo**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The sorting order is the same as described in the **sort** function above.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The **min_by(path_exp)** and **max_by(path_exp)** functions allow you to specify a particular field or property to examine, e.g.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] **min_by(.foo)** finds the object with the smallest **foo** field.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The **unique** function takes as input an array and produces an array of the same elements, in sorted order, with duplicates removed.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The **unique_by(path_exp)** function will keep only one element for each value obtained by applying the argument.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] Think of it as making an array by taking one element out of every group produced by **group**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The filter **contains(b)** will produce true if b is completely contained within the input.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] Outputs an array containing the indices in **.** where **s** occurs.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] The input may be an array, in which case if **s** is an array then the indices output will be those where all elements in **.** match those of **s**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p01] Outputs the index of the first (**index**) or last (**rindex**) occurrence of **s** in the input.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The filter **inside(b)** will produce true if the input is completely contained within b.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] It is, essentially, an inversed version of **contains**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] Outputs **true** if . starts with the given string argument.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] Outputs **true** if . ends with the given string argument.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] If given an argument **n**, it outputs all combinations of **n** repetitions of the input array.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] Whitespace characters are the usual **" "**, **"\n"** **"\t"**, **"\r"** and also all characters in the Unicode character database with the whitespace property.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] Converts an input string into an array of the string´s codepoint numbers.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] It is the inverse of **split**: that is, running **split("foo") | join("foo")** over any input string returns said input string.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The **while(cond; update)** function allows you to repeatedly apply an update to **.** until **cond** is false.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] Note that **while(cond; update)** is internally defined as a recursive jq function.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] Recursive calls within **while** will not consume additional memory if **update** produces at most one output for each input.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The **repeat(exp)** function allows you to repeatedly apply expression **exp** to **.** until an error is raised.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] Note that **repeat(exp)** is internally defined as a recursive jq function.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] Recursive calls within **repeat** will not consume additional memory if **exp** produces at most one output for each input.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The **until(cond; next)** function allows you to repeatedly apply the expression **next**, initially to **.** then to its own output, until **cond** is true.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] Note that **until(cond; next)** is internally defined as a recursive jq function.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] Recursive calls within **until()** will not consume additional memory if **next** produces at most one output for each input.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The **recurse(f)** function allows you to search through a recursive structure, and extract interesting data from all levels.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] When called without an argument, **recurse** is equivalent to **recurse(.[]?)**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The recursive calls in **recurse** will not consume additional memory whenever **f** produces at most a single output for each input.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The **walk(f)** function applies f recursively to every component of the input entity.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] This builtin returns true if jq´s build configuration includes support for preservation of input number literals.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] This builtin binding shows the jq executable´s build configuration.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] Its value has no particular format, but it can be expected to be at least the **./configure** command-line arguments, and may be enriched in the future to include the version strings for the build tooling used.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] Note that this can be overridden in the command-line with **--arg** and related options.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The **tojson** and **fromjson** builtins dump values as JSON texts or parse JSON texts into values, respectively.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The **tojson** builtin differs from **tostring** in that **tostring** returns strings unmodified, while **tojson** encodes strings as JSON strings.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The **@foo** syntax is used to format and escape strings, which is useful for building URLs, documents in a language like HTML or XML, and so forth.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] sequences to their corresponding URI characters.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] , input is decoded as specified by RFC 4648.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] You can follow a **@foo** token with a string literal.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The **fromdateiso8601** builtin parses datetimes in the ISO 8601 format to a number of seconds since the Unix epoch (1970-01-01T00:00:00Z).
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The **todateiso8601** builtin does the inverse.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The **fromdate** builtin parses datetime strings.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] Currently **fromdate** only supports ISO 8601 datetime strings, but in the future it will attempt to parse datetime strings in more formats.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The **todate** builtin is an alias for **todateiso8601**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The **now** builtin outputs the current time, in seconds since the Unix epoch.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] Low-level jq interfaces to the C-library time functions are also provided: **strptime**, **strftime**, **strflocaltime**, **mktime**, **gmtime**, and **localtime**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] Refer to your host operating system´s documentation for the format strings used by **strptime** and **strftime**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The **localtime** builtin works like the **gmtime** builtin, but using the local timezone setting.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The **mktime** builtin consumes "broken down time" representations of time output by **gmtime** and **strptime**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The **strptime(fmt)** builtin parses input strings matching the **fmt** argument.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The output is in the "broken down time" representation consumed by **mktime** and output by **gmtime**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The **strftime(fmt)** builtin formats a time (GMT) with the given format.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The **strflocaltime** does the same, but using the local timezone setting.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The format strings for **strptime** and **strftime** are described in typical C library documentation.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] In particular, the **%u** and **%j** specifiers for **strptime(fmt)** are not supported on macOS.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The index´s keys are computed by applying the given index expression to each value from the given stream.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] Returns a list of all builtin functions in the format **name/arity**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] Since functions with the same name but different arities are considered separate functions, **all/0**, **all/1**, and **all/2** would all be present in the list.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The expression ´a == b´ will produce ´true´ if the results of evaluating a and b are equal (that is, if they represent equivalent JSON values) and ´false´ otherwise.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] If you´re coming from JavaScript, please note that jq´s **==** is like JavaScript´s **===**, the "strict equality" operator.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] Checking for false or null is a simpler notion of "truthiness" than is found in JavaScript or Python, but it means that you´ll sometimes have to be more explicit about the condition you want.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] You can´t test whether, e.g. a string is empty using **if .name then A else B end**; you´ll need something like **if .name == "" then A else B end** instead.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] If the condition **A** produces multiple results, then **B** is evaluated once for each result that is not false or null, and **C** is evaluated once for each false or null.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] More cases can be added to an if using **elif A then B** syntax.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The comparison operators **>**, **>=**, **<=**, **<** return whether their left argument is greater than, greater than or equal to, less than or equal to or less than their right argument (respectively).
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The ordering is the same as that described for **sort**, above.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] jq supports the normal Boolean operators **and**, **or**, **not**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] They have the same standard of truth as if expressions - **false** and **null** are considered "false values", and anything else is a "true value".
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] These three only produce the values **true** and **false**, and so are only useful for genuine Boolean operations, rather than the common Perl/Python/Ruby idiom of "value_that_may_be_null or default".
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] If you want to use this form of "or", picking between two values rather than evaluating a condition, see the **//** operator below.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The **//** operator produces all the values of its left-hand side that are neither **false** nor **null**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] If the left-hand side produces no values other than **false** or **null**, then **//** produces all the values of its right-hand side.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] A filter of the form **a // b** produces all the results of **a** that are not **false** or **null**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] If **a** produces no results, or no results other than **false** or **null**, then **a // b** produces the results of **b**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] This is useful for providing defaults: **.foo // 1** will evaluate to **1** if there´s no **.foo** element in the input.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] It´s similar to how **or** is sometimes used in Python (jq´s **or** operator is reserved for strictly Boolean operations).
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] Note: **some_generator // defaults_here** is not the same as **some_generator | . // defaults_here**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The latter will produce default values for all non-**false**, non-**null** values of the left-hand side, while the former will not.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] In **(false, null, 1) | . // 42** the left-hand side of **//** is **.**, which always produces just one value, while in **(false, null, 1) // 42** the left-hand side is a generator of three values, and since it produces a value other **false** and **null**, the default **42** is not produced.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] Errors can be caught by using **try EXP catch EXP**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The **try EXP** form uses **empty** as the exception handler.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] A convenient use of try/catch is to break out of control structures like **reduce**, **foreach**, **while**, and so on.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The **break $label_name** expression will cause the program to act as though the nearest (to the left) **label $label_name** produced **empty**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The relationship between the **break** and corresponding **label** is lexical: the label has to be "visible" from the break.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The **?** operator, used as **EXP?**, is shorthand for **try EXP**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] For example, the regular expression **\s** signifying a whitespace character would be written as **"\\s"**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] To match a whitespace with the **x** flag, use **\s**, e.g.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] Like **match**, but does not return match objects, only **true** or **false** for whether or not the regex matches the input.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] To capture all the matches for each input string, use the idiom **[ expr ]**, e.g.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] For backwards compatibility, when called with a single argument, **split** splits on a string, not a regex.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] These provide the same results as their **split** counterparts, but as a stream instead of an array.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] Emit the string obtained by replacing the first match of regex in the input string with **tostring**, after interpolation.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] **tostring** should be a jq string or a stream of such strings, each of which may contain references to named captures.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The named captures are, in effect, presented as a JSON object (as constructed by **capture**) to **tostring**, so a reference to a captured variable named "x" would take the form: **"\(.x)"**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] Variables are an absolute necessity in most programming languages, but they´re relegated to an "advanced feature" in jq.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] If you calculate a value, and you want to use it more than once, you´ll need to store it in a variable.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] To pass a value to another part of the program, you´ll need that part of the program to define a variable (as a function parameter, object member, or whatever) in which to place the data.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] It is also possible to define functions in jq, although this is is a feature whose biggest use is defining jq´s standard library (many jq functions such as **map** and **select** are in fact written in jq).
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] Again, these are mostly used internally, to define some useful bits of jq´s standard library.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] Many expressions, for instance **a + b**, pass their input to two distinct subexpressions (here **a** and **b** are both passed the same input), so variables aren´t usually necessary in order to use a value twice.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] In jq, it´s simply **add / length** - the **add** expression is given the array and produces its sum, and the **length** expression is given the array and produces its length.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] So, there´s generally a cleaner way to solve most problems in jq than defining variables.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] Still, sometimes they do make things easier, so jq lets you define variables using **expression as $variable**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] We´ll need a more complicated problem to find a situation where using variables actually makes our lives easier.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The expression **exp as $x | ...** means: for each value of expression **exp**, run the rest of the pipeline with the entire original input, and with **$x** set to that value.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] Thus **as** functions as something of a foreach loop.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] Just as **{foo}** is a handy way of writing **{foo: .foo}**, so **{$foo}** is a handy way of writing **{foo: $foo}**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The variable declarations in array patterns (e.g., **. as [$first, $second]**) bind to the elements of the array in from the element at index zero on up, in order.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] When there is no value at the index for an array pattern element, **null** is bound to that variable.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] For programming language theorists, it´s more accurate to say that jq variables are lexically-scoped bindings.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] In particular there´s no way to change the value of a binding; one can only setup a new binding with the same name, but which will not be visible where the old one was.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] From then on, **increment** is usable as a filter just like a builtin function (in fact, this is how many of the builtins are defined).
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The same argument may be referenced multiple times with different inputs (here **f** is run for each element of the input array).
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The result will be 20 because **f** is **.*2**, and during the first invocation of **f** **.** will be 5, and the second time it will be 10 (5 * 2), so the result will be 20.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] With either definition, **addvalue(.foo)** will add the current input´s **.foo** field to each element of the array.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] Do note that calling **addvalue(.[])** will cause the **map(. + $f)** part to be evaluated once per value in the value of **.** at the call site.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] For example, in the following expression there is a binding which is visible "to the right" of it, **... | .*3 as $times_three | [. + $times_three] | ...**, but not "to the left".
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] Consider this expression now, **... | (.*3 as $times_three | [. + $times_three]) | ...**: here the binding **$times_three** is *not* visible past the closing parenthesis.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] Returns true if **exp** produces no outputs, false otherwise.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The **limit** function extracts up to **n** outputs from **expr**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The **skip** function skips the first **n** outputs from **expr**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The **first(expr)** and **last(expr)** functions extract the first and last values from **expr**, respectively.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The **nth(n; expr)** function extracts the nth value output by **expr**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] Note that **nth(n; expr)** doesn´t support negative values of **n**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The **first** and **last** functions extract the first and last values from any array at **.**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The **nth(n)** function extracts the nth value of any array at **.**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The **reduce** syntax allows you to combine all of the results of an expression by accumulating them into a single answer.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The form is **reduce EXP as $var (INIT; UPDATE)**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] For each result that **.[]** produces, **. + $item** is run to accumulate a running total, starting from 0 as the input value.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The **foreach** syntax is similar to **reduce**, but intended to allow the construction of **limit** and reducers that produce intermediate results.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The form is **foreach EXP as $var (INIT; UPDATE; EXTRACT)**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] Like the **reduce** syntax, **. + $item** is run for each result that **.[]** produces, but **[$item, .
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] * 2]** is run for each intermediate values.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] When **EXTRACT** is omitted, the identity filter is used.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] As described above, **recurse** uses recursion, and any jq function can be recursive.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p02] The **while** builtin is also implemented in terms of recursion.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] For example, **.[]** generates all the values in its input (which must be an array or an object), **range(0; 10)** generates the integers between 0 and 10, and so on.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] The **empty** builtin is the generator that produces zero outputs.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] The **empty** builtin backtracks to the preceding generator expression.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] In the example below the recursive call by **_range** to itself is in tail position.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] Besides simple arithmetic operators such as **+**, jq also has most standard math functions from the C math library.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] C math functions that take a single input argument (e.g., **sin()**) are available as zero-argument jq functions.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] C math functions that take two input arguments (e.g., **pow()**) are available as two-argument jq functions that ignore **.**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] C math functions that take three input arguments are available as three-argument jq functions that ignore **.**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] See your system´s manual for more information on each of these.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] Two builtins functions are provided for this, **input** and **inputs**, that read from the same sources (e.g., **stdin**, files named on the command-line) as jq itself.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] These two builtins, and jq´s own reading actions, can be interleaved with each other.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] They are commonly used in combination with the null input option **-n** to prevent one input from being read implicitly.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] Two builtins provide minimal output capabilities, **debug**, and **stderr**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] (Recall that a jq program´s output values are always output as JSON texts on **stdout**.) The **debug** builtin can have application-specific behavior, such as for executables that use the libjq C API but aren´t the jq executable itself.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] The **stderr** builtin outputs its input in raw mode to stderr with no additional decoration, not even a newline.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] Note that when using **input** it is generally necessary to invoke jq with the **-n** command-line option, otherwise the first entity will be lost.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] This is primarily useful for reductions over a program´s inputs.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] Note that when using **inputs** it is generally necessary to invoke jq with the **-n** command-line option, otherwise the first entity will be lost.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] These two filters are like **.** but have as a side-effect the production of one or more messages on stderr.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] where **<input-value>** is a compact rendition of the input value.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] The **debug(msgs)** filter is defined as **(msgs | debug | empty), .** thus allowing great flexibility in the content of the message, while also allowing multi-line debugging statements to be created.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] With the **--stream** option jq can parse input texts in a streaming fashion, allowing jq programs to start processing large JSON texts immediately rather than after the parse completes.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] However, streaming isn´t easy to deal with as the jq program will have **[<path>, <leaf-value>]** (and a few other forms) as inputs.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] Streaming forms include **[<path>, <leaf-value>]** (to indicate any scalar value, empty array, or empty object), and **[<path>]** (to indicate the end of an array or object).
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] Future versions of jq run with **--stream** and **--seq** may output additional forms such as **["error message"]** when an input text fails to parse.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] Outputs values corresponding to the stream expression´s outputs.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] The **tostream** builtin outputs the streamed form of its input.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] Assignment works a little differently in jq than in most programming languages. jq doesn´t distinguish between references to and copies of something - two objects or arrays are either equal or not equal, without any further notion of being "the same object" or "not the same object".
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] If an object has two fields which are arrays, **.foo** and **.bar**, and you append something to **.foo**, then **.bar** will not get bigger, even if you´ve previously set **.bar = .foo**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] If you´re used to programming in languages like Python, Java, Ruby, JavaScript, etc. then you can think of it as though jq does a full deep copy of every object before it does the assignment (for performance it doesn´t actually do that, but that´s the general idea).
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] This means that it´s impossible to build circular values in jq (such as an array whose first element is itself).
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] Internally, assignment works by using a reduction to compute new, replacement values for **.** that have had all the desired assignments applied to **.**, then outputting the modified value.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] Most users will want to use modification assignment operators, such as **|=** or **+=**, rather than **=**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] Note that the LHS of assignment operators refers to a value in **.**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] Thus **$var.foo = 1** won´t work as expected (**$var.foo** is not a valid or useful path expression in **.**); use **$var | .foo = 1** instead.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] It takes a filter on the right-hand side and works out the new value for the property of **.** being assigned to by running the old value through this expression.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] For instance, **(.foo, .bar) |= .+1** will build an object with the **foo** field set to the input´s **foo** plus 1, and the **bar** field set to the input´s **bar** plus 1.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] The left-hand side can be any general path expression; see **path()**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] Note that the left-hand side of **|=** refers to a value in **.**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] Thus **$var.foo |= . + 1** won´t work as expected (**$var.foo** is not a valid or useful path expression in **.**); use **$var | .foo |= . + 1** instead.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] If the right-hand side outputs no values (i.e., **empty**), then the left-hand side path will be deleted, as with **del(path)**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] jq has a few operators of the form **a op= b**, which are all equivalent to **a |= . op b**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] So, **+= 1** can be used to increment values, being the same as **|= . + 1**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] If the RHS of **=** produces multiple values, then for each such value jq will set the paths on the left-hand side to the value and then it will output the modified **.**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] The former will set the **a** field of the input to the **b** field of the input, and produce the output **{"a": 20, "b": 20}**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] The latter will set the **a** field of the input to the **a** field´s **b** field, producing **{"a": 10, "b": 20}**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] When jq encounters an assignment like ´a = b´, it records the "path" taken to select a part of the input document while executing a.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] You can write comments in your jq filters using **#**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] A **#** character (not part of a string) starts a comment.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] All characters from **#** to the end of the line are ignored.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] If the end of the line is preceded by an odd number of backslash characters, the following line is also considered part of the comment and is ignored.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] The **exec** line is considered a comment by jq, so it is ignored.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] But it is not ignored by **sh**, since in **sh** a backslash at the end of the line does not continue the comment.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] Modules are files whose names end in **.jq**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] The **import** and **include** directives allow the importer to alter this path.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] For paths starting with **~/**, the user´s home directory is substituted for **~**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] For paths starting with **$ORIGIN/**, the directory where the jq executable is located is substituted for **$ORIGIN**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] For paths starting with **./** or paths that are **.**, the path of the including file is substituted for **.**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] The default search path is the search path given to the **-L** command-line option, else **["~/.jq", "$ORIGIN/../lib/jq", "$ORIGIN/../lib"]**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] A dependency with relative path **foo/bar** would be searched for in **foo/bar.jq** and **foo/bar/bar.jq** in the given search path.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] Consecutive components with the same name are not allowed to avoid ambiguities (e.g., **foo/foo**).
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] If **.jq** exists in the user´s home directory, and is a file (not a directory), it is automatically sourced into the main program.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] A **.jq** suffix will be added to the relative path string.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] The module´s symbols are prefixed with **NAME::**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] It should be an object with keys like **homepage** and so on.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] At this time jq only uses the **search** key/value of the metadata.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] The metadata is also made available to users via the **modulemeta** builtin.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] The **search** key in the metadata, if present, should have a string or array value (array of strings); this is the search path to be prefixed to the top-level search path.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] The module´s symbols are imported into the caller´s namespace as if the module´s content had been included directly.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] A **.json** suffix will be added to the relative path string.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] The file´s data will be available as **$NAME::NAME**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] It serves only the purpose of providing metadata that can be read with the **modulemeta** builtin.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] It should be an object with keys like **homepage**.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] At this time jq doesn´t use this metadata, but it is made available to users via the **modulemeta** builtin.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] Takes a module name as input and outputs the module´s metadata as an object, with the module´s imports (including metadata) as an array value for the **deps** key and the module´s defined functions as an array value for the **defs** key.
[src:jq-json/man-jq-p03] Programs can use this to query a module´s metadata, which they could then use to, for example, search for, download, and install missing dependencies.
